ota Auto Body]]\n  | [[Toyota Financial Services]]\n  | [[Toyota Motor East Japan]]\n  | '''International:'''\n  | [[Indus Motors Company|Toyota Pakistan]]\n  | [[Toyota-Astra Motor]] (Indonesia)\n  | [[Toyota Motor North America]]\n  | [[Toyota Kirloskar Motor|Toyota Kirloskar India]] (89%)\n  | [[Toyota Canada Inc.|Toyota Canada]] (51%)\n  | [[Toyota Motor Sales, U.S.A., Inc.|Toyota Motor Sales USA]]\n  | [[Toyota Motor Europe]]\n  | [[Toyota Manufacturing UK|Toyota Motor Manufacturing UK]]\n  | [[Toyota (GB) PLC]]\n  | [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing France]]\n  | [[Toyota Motor Philippines]]\n  | [[Toyota Motor Thailand]] (86.43%)\n  | [[Toyota Peugeot Citro\u00ebn Automobile Czech]] (50%)\n  | [[Toyota Motor (Russia)|Toyota Motor Russia]]\n  | [[Toyota Motor Corporation Australia]]\n  | [[Toyota South Africa Motors]]\n  | [[Perodua]] (25%)\n  }}\n| homepage = {{URL|toyota-global.com}}\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1937|08|28|df=yes}}\n| location_city = [[Toyota City]]\n| location_country = Japan\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Toyota Motor Corporation'''\n|\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u81ea\u52d5\u8eca\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Toyota Jid\u014dsha [[Kabushiki gaisha|KK]]|{{IPA-ja|to\ua71cjota|IPA}}, {{IPAc-en|lang|t|\u0254\u026a|\u02c8|o\u028a|t|\u0259}}|lead=yes}} is a Japanese [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[Automotive industry|automotive]] manufacturer headquartered in [[Toyota, Aichi]], Japan. <!--Cited below--> In 2017, Toyota's corporate structure consisted of 364,445 employees worldwide<ref name=fortune>{{cite web |url=http://fortune.com/global500/toyota-motor/ |title=Toyota Motor (TM) Stock Price, Financials and News |work=Global 500 |publisher=Fortune |location=US |access-date=January 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411171619/http://fortune.com/global500/toyota-motor/ |archive-date=April 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and, {{as of|lc=y|2019|12}}, was the [[List of largest companies by revenue|tenth-largest company in the world by revenue]]. Toyota is the second largest automobile manufacturer in the world, behind Volkswagen, based on 2018 unit sales.<ref>{{cite web |title=The World's Largest Car Manufacturers |url=https://www.manufacturing.net/automotive/article/13251666/the-worlds-largest-car-manufacturers |website=Statista |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> Toyota was the world's first automobile manufacturer to produce more than 10 million vehicles per year, which it has done since 2012, when it also reported the production of its 200-millionth vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |first=Malcolm |last=Flynn |url=http://www.themotorreport.com.au/54659/toyota-77-years-200-million-vehicles |title=Toyota Announces Its 200 Millionth Vehicle After 77 Years Of Production &#124; Reviews &#124; Prices &#124; Australian specifications |publisher=Themotorreport.com.au |date=July 25, 2012 |accessdate=September 9, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728140733/http://www.themotorreport.com.au/54659/toyota-77-years-200-million-vehicles |archive-date=July 28, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2014|07}}, Toyota was the largest listed company in Japan by [[market capitalization]] (worth more than twice as much as number 2-ranked [[SoftBank Corp.|SoftBank]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.finance.yahoo.co.jp/ranking/?kd=4&mk=1&tm=d&vl=a |script-title=ja:\u6642\u4fa1\u7dcf\u984d\u4e0a\u4f4d\uff1a\u682a\u5f0f\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 |trans-title=Market capitalization: Top stock rankings |publisher=Yahoo |location=Japan |language=Japanese |accessdate=July 21, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001020043/http://info.finance.yahoo.co.jp/ranking/?kd=4&mk=1&tm=d&vl=a |archive-date=October 1, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and by revenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.finance.yahoo.co.jp/ranking/?kd=46&mk=1&tm=d&vl=a |script-title=ja:\u58f2\u4e0a\u9ad8\uff1a\u682a\u5f0f\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 |trans-title=Sales: stock rankings |publisher=Yahoo |location=Japan |language=Japanese |accessdate=July 21, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001041754/http://info.finance.yahoo.co.jp/ranking/?kd=46&mk=1&tm=d&vl=a |archive-date=October 1, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/toyota-motor/ |title=Toyota Motor on the Forbes World's Most Valuable Brands List |work=Forbes |date=May 2015 |accessdate=May 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622162537/http://www.forbes.com/companies/toyota-motor/ |archive-date=June 22, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nToyota is the global market leader in sales of [[hybrid electric vehicle]]s, and one of the largest companies to encourage the mass-market adoption of hybrid vehicles across the globe. Toyota is also a market leader in [[Hydrogen vehicle|hydrogen fuel-cell]] vehicles. Cumulative global sales of Toyota and [[Lexus]] hybrid passenger car models achieved the 10&nbsp;million milestone in January 2017. Its [[Prius family]] is the world's top-selling hybrid [[nameplate]] with over 6&nbsp;million units sold worldwide {{as of|2017|01|lc=y}}.<ref name=TMC10miHEVs/>\n\nThe company was founded by [[Kiichiro Toyoda]] in 1937, as a spinoff from [[Sakichi Toyoda|his father's]] company [[Toyota Industries]] to create [[automobiles]]. Three years earlier, in 1934, while still a department of Toyota Industries, it created its first product, the [[Toyota Type A engine|Type A engine]], and its first passenger car in 1936, the [[Toyota AA]]. Toyota Motor Corporation produces vehicles under five brands, including the Toyota brand, [[Hino Motors|Hino]], Lexus, [[Ranz]], and [[Daihatsu]]. It also holds a 16.66% stake in [[Subaru Corporation]], a 5.9% stake in [[Isuzu]] until 2018, a 5.5% stake in [[Mazda]], a 4.9% stake in [[Suzuki]], as well as joint-ventures with two in China ([[GAC Toyota]] and [[Sichuan FAW Toyota Motor]]), one in India ([[Toyota Kirloskar Motor|Toyota Kirloskar]]), one in the Czech Republic ([[Toyota Peugeot Citro\u00ebn Automobile Czech|TPCA]]), along with several \"nonautomotive\" companies.<ref name=\"Toyota: Non-Automotive\">{{cite web |url=http://www.toyota.co.jp/en/index_non_automotive.html |title=Toyota: Non-Automotive |publisher=Toyota Motor Corporation |location=Japan |accessdate=August 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205043613/http://www.toyota.co.jp/en/index_non_automotive.html |archive-date=December 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> TMC is part of the [[Toyota Group]], one of the largest conglomerates in Japan.\n\nToyota is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]], [[New York Stock Exchange]] and [[Tokyo Stock Exchange]].\n\n==Corporate governance==\n[[File:Headquarter of Toyota Motor Corporation 4.JPG|thumb|Principal headquarters building of Toyota]]\n\nToyota is headquartered in [[Toyota City]], [[Aichi Prefecture|Aichi]].<ref name=Toyotaprofile>{{cite web |url=http://www.toyota-global.com/company/profile/overview/ |title=Overview |publisher=Toyota Motor Corporation |work=Global website |date=March 31, 2014 |accessdate=February 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213041727/http://www.toyota-global.com/company/profile/overview/ |archive-date=February 13, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The main headquarters of Toyota is located in a 4-story building in Toyota. As of 2006, the head office has the \"Toyopet\" Toyota logo and the words \"Toyota Motor\". The Toyota Technical Center, a 14-story building, and the Honsha plant, Toyota's second plant engaging in mass production and formerly named the Koromo plant, are adjacent to one another in a location near the headquarters. Vinod Jacob from ''[[The Hindu]]'' described the main headquarters building as \"modest\".<ref name=Jacob>{{cite news |last=Jacob |first=Vinod |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/life/2006/08/18/stories/2006081800020200.htm |title=In Toyota land |work=[[The Hindu]] \u2013 [[Business Line]] |date=August 18, 2006 |accessdate=May 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721173402/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/life/2006/08/18/stories/2006081800020200.htm |archivedate=July 21, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2013, company head Akio Toyoda reported that it had difficulties retaining foreign employees at the headquarters due to the lack of amenities in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last=Greimel |first=Hans |url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130506/GLOBAL02/305069976/dreary-hq-city-is-a-handicap-in-global-glitz-plan#axzz2SrMwuTWn |title=Dreary HQ city is a handicap in global glitz plan |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130616011434/http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130506/GLOBAL02/305069976/dreary-hq-city-is-a-handicap-in-global-glitz-plan%23axzz2SrMwuTWn |archivedate=June 16, 2013 |work=[[Automotive News]] |date=May 6, 2013 |accessdate=May 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIts Tokyo office is located in [[Bunkyo, Tokyo|Bunkyo]], Tokyo. Its [[Nagoya]] office is located in [[Nakamura-ku, Nagoya|Nakamura-ku]], Nagoya.<ref name=Toyotaprofile/> In addition to manufacturing automobiles, Toyota provides [[financial services]] through its [[Toyota Financial Services]] [[division (business)|division]], and also builds robots.\n\n[[File:Akio Toyoda.jpg|thumb|Akio Toyoda, CEO of Toyota, at the annual results press conference, May 11, 2011]]\n[[File:Toyota global network.svg|thumb|Toyota's global network:<br />Red \u2013 Japan<br /> Green \u2013 Official dealership(s) present.<br /> Blue \u2013 Localized manufacturing plant(s)<br /> Cyan \u2013 Regional headquarters (HQ)<br /> Purple \u2013 Regional headquarters (HQ) and localized manufacturing plants]]\n[[File:Toyota sales.gif|thumb|Typical breakdown of sales by region]]\n\nPresidents of Toyota Motor Company:\n* [[Rizaburo Toyoda]] (1937\u20131941)\n* [[Kiichiro Toyoda]] (1941\u20131950)\n* [[Taizo Ishida]] (1950\u20131961)\n* [[Fukio Nakagawa]] (1961\u20131967)\n* [[Eiji Toyoda]] (1967\u20131982)\n\nIn 1981, Toyota Motor Co., Ltd. announced plans to merge with its sales entity Toyota Motor Sales Co., Ltd. Since 1950, the two entities had existed as separate companies as a prerequisite for reconstruction in postwar Japan. Shoichiro Toyoda presided over Toyota Motor Sales in preparation for the consummation of the merger that occurred in 1982. Shoichiro then succeeded his uncle Eiji as the president of the combined organization that then became known as Toyota Motor Corporation.\n\nPresidents of Toyota Motor Corporation:\n* [[Eiji Toyoda]] (1981)\n* [[Shoichiro Toyoda]] (1982\u20131992)<ref name=Tatsuro/>\n* [[Tatsuro Toyoda]] (1992\u20131995)<ref name=Tatsuro>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/29/business/brother-to-get-post-at-toyota.html |title=Brother to Get Post at Toyota |work=The New York Times |date=July 29, 1992 |accessdate=December 26, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226215458/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/29/business/brother-to-get-post-at-toyota.html |archive-date=December 26, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Hiroshi Okuda]] (1995\u20131999)\n* [[Fujio Cho]] (1999\u20132005)\n* [[Katsuaki Watanabe]] (2005\u20132009)\n* [[Akio Toyoda]] (2009\u2013present)\n\nChairmen of Toyota Motor Corporation:\n* [[Shoichiro Toyoda]] (1992\u20131999)\n* [[Hiroshi Okuda]] (1999\u20132006)\n* [[Fujio Cho]] (2006\u20132013)\n* [[Takeshi Uchiyamada]] (2013\u2013present)\n\nOn June 14, 2013, Toyota Motor Corporation. announced the appointment of external board members; this was a first for the corporation and occurred following approval from general shareholders at a meeting on the same day. Additionally, Vice Chairman Takeshi Uchiyamada replaced Fujio Cho as chairman, as the latter became an honorary chairman while Toyoda remains in the post of president.<ref>{{cite news |title=BIZ BRIEF: Toyota appoints first outside board members |url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/economy/biz_briefs/AJ201306140081 |accessdate=June 14, 2013 |newspaper=The Asahi Shimbun |date=June 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908224850/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/economy/biz_briefs/AJ201306140081 |archivedate=September 8, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nToyota is publicly traded on the [[Tokyo Stock Exchange|Tokyo]], [[Osaka Stock Exchange|Osaka]], [[Nagoya Stock Exchange|Nagoya]], [[Fukuoka]], and [[Sapporo]] exchanges under company code {{Tyo|7203}}. In addition, Toyota is foreign-listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] under {{nyse|TM}} and on the [[London Stock Exchange]] under {{Lse|TYT}}. Toyota has been publicly traded in Japan since 1949 and internationally since 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toyota.co.jp/en/ir/faq/share.html |title=Toyota for investors, Frequently Asked Questions |accessdate=July 2, 2008 |publisher=Toyota Motor Corporation |location=Japan |date=February 2, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617074029/http://www.toyota.co.jp/en/ir/faq/share.html |archive-date=June 17, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs reported on its consolidated financial statements, Toyota has 606 consolidated subsidiaries and 199 affiliates.<ref name=20f />\n* [[Toyota Motor North America]] (100% \u2013 2004)\n* [[Toyota Canada Inc.]] (51% \u2013 2013)\n* [[Toyota Tsusho]] \u2013 Trading company for the Toyota Group\n* [[Daihatsu Motor Company]] (100%)\n* [[Hino Motors]] (50.1% \u2013 2001)\n* [[Lexus]] 100% (1989)\n* [[Scion (automobile)|Scion]] 100% (2003)\n* [[DENSO]] (24.74% \u2013 September 30, 2006)\n* [[Toyota Industries]] (23.51% \u2013 March 31, 2006)\n* [[Aisin Seiki Co.]] (23.0% \u2013 September 30, 2006)\n* [[Subaru Corporation]] (16.66% \u2013 June 28, 2008)\n* [[Isuzu Motors]] (5.9% \u2013 November 10, 2006)\n* [[Toyota Astra Motor|PT Toyota Astra Motor]] (50% \u2013 2017)\n* [[Noble Automotive]] (23% \u2013 2014)\n* [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing Indonesia|PT Toyota Motor Manufacturing Indonesia]]<ref name=\"investvine\">{{cite web |url=http://investvine.com/toyota-builds-new-engine-plant-in-indonesia/ |title=Toyota builds new engine plant in Indonesia |first=Arno |last=Maierbrugger |work=Inside Investor |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=July 24, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808120810/http://investvine.com/toyota-builds-new-engine-plant-in-indonesia/ |archive-date=August 8, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> (95% \u2013 2003)\n\n===Global ranking===\nToyota, which earlier was [[List of manufacturers by motor vehicle production|the world's third-largest automotive manufacturer]] behind American [[General Motors]] and [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], produced for the first time in history more vehicles than Ford in 2005, and in 2006 even more than General Motors and has been the world's largest automotive manufacturer since then, except in 2011 when, triggered by the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]], it fell to the number 3 position behind General Motors and German [[Volkswagen Group]].\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Toyota}}\n\n===1920s{{ndash}}1930s===\n[[File:Toyota Loom Mass Production Bertel Schmitt.jpg|thumb|The mass-produced Toyoda automated loom, displayed at Toyota Museum in Aichi-gun, Japan]]\nIn 1924, [[Sakichi Toyoda]] invented the Toyoda Model G Automatic [[Loom]]. The principle of ''[[jidoka]]'', which means the machine stops itself when a problem occurs, became later a part of the [[Toyota Production System]]. Looms were built on a small [[production line]]. In 1929, the patent for the automatic loom was sold to the British company [[Platt Brothers]],<ref>{{cite web |title=The Story of Sakichi Toyoda |url=https://www.toyota-industries.com/company/history/toyoda_sakichi/index.html |publisher=Toyota Industries Corporation |access-date=September 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923003201/https://www.toyota-industries.com/company/history/toyoda_sakichi/index.html |archive-date=September 23, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> generating the starting capital for automobile development.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toyota-global.com/company/history_of_toyota/ |title=History Of Toyota |publisher=Toyota |access-date=August 15, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812013404/http://www.toyota-global.com/company/history_of_toyota/ |archive-date=August 12, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Toyoda Standard Sedan AA 1936 Bertel Schmitt.jpg|thumb|Toyoda Standard Sedan AA 1936]]\n\nThe production of Toyota automobiles was started in 1933 as a division of [[Toyota Industries|Toyoda Automatic Loom Works]] devoted to the production of automobiles under the direction of the founder's son, [[Kiichiro Toyoda]].<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510085717/http://www.toyota-global.com/company/history_of_toyota |archivedate=May 10, 2013 |url=http://www.toyota.co.jp/en/history/1867.html |title=Toyota Company History from 1867 to 1939 |publisher=Toyota |accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref> Its first vehicles were the [[Toyota A1|A1]] passenger [[car]] and the [[Toyota G1|G1]] [[truck]] in 1935. The Toyota Motor Company was established as an independent company in 1937\nVehicles were originally sold under the name \"Toyoda\" (\u30c8\u30e8\u30c0), from the family name of the company's founder, [[Kiichiro Toyoda|Kiichir\u014d Toyoda]]. In April 1936, Toyoda's first passenger car, the [[Toyota AA|Model AA]], was completed. The sales price was 3,350 yen, 400 yen cheaper than [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] or [[General Motors|GM]] cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toyota.co.jp/Museum/data_e/a03_08_1.html |title=Information from a sign at the Toyota Museum in Nagakute-cho, Aichi-gun, Aichi Pref |publisher=Toyota |date=|accessdate=December 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120220844/http://www.toyota.co.jp/Museum/data_e/a03_08_1.html |archivedate=November 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1936, the company ran a public competition to design a new logo. Of 27,000 entries, the winning entry was the three Japanese ''[[katakana]]'' letters for \"Toyoda\" in a circle. However, [[Rizaburo Toyoda]], who had [[mukoy\u014dshi|married into the family]] and was not born with that name, preferred \"Toyota\" ({{nihongo2|\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf}}) because it took eight brush strokes (a lucky number) to write in Japanese, was visually simpler (leaving off the [[Dakuten|diacritic]] at the end), and with a [[voiceless|voiceless consonant]] instead of a [[voice (phonetics)|voiced]] one (voiced consonants are considered to have a \"murky\" or \"muddy\" sound compared to voiceless consonants, which are \"clear\").\n\nSince ''toyoda'' literally means \"fertile rice paddies\", changing the name also prevented the company from being associated with old-fashioned farming. The newly formed word was trademarked and the company was registered in August 1937 as the Toyota Motor Company.<ref name=Davis>{{cite book |title=The Long Run \u2013 Toyota: The first 40 years in Australia |first=Pedr |last=Davis |location=South Hurstville |publisher=Type Forty Pty Ltd |year=1999 |isbn=0-947079-99-8 |page=24}}</ref><ref name=fiftyyears64>{{cite book |title=Toyota: A history of the First 50 Years |publisher=Toyota |year=1988 |isbn=0-517-61777-3 |page=64}}</ref><ref name=Dawson>{{cite book |first=Chester |last=Dawson |year=2004 |title=Lexus: The Relentless Pursuit |location=Singapore |publisher=John Wiley &amp}}</ref>\n\n===1940s\u20131950s===\n[[File:1955 Toyopet Crown 03.jpg|thumb|First-generation Toyopet Crown Model RSD (1955/1 \u2013 1958/10)]]\n\nFrom September 1947, Toyota's small-sized vehicles were sold under the name \"Toyopet\" (\u30c8\u30e8\u30da\u30c3\u30c8).<ref name=archive96>{{cite web |url=http://toyota.jpn.org/archives/96 |title=Toyota Holders |date=June 4, 2007 |publisher=Toyota |location=Japan |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123192025/http://toyota.jpn.org/archives/96 |archive-date=January 23, 2009 }}</ref> The first vehicle sold under this name was the [[Toyota SA|Toyopet SA]],<ref name=fiftyyears102>''Toyota: A history of the First 50 Years'', Toyota Motor Corporation, 1988, {{ISBN|0-517-61777-3}}, p. 102.</ref> but it also included vehicles such as the [[Toyota SB|Toyopet SB]] light truck, [[Toyota Stout|Toyopet Stout]] light truck,<ref name=stout>\"Toyota Truck 48HP\", Toyota brochure No. 228, Japan</ref> [[Toyota Crown|Toyopet Crown]], [[Toyopet Master]], and the [[Toyota Corona|Toyopet Corona]]. The word \"Toyopet\" ([[:ja:\u30c8\u30e8\u30da\u30c3\u30c8 (\u30d6\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9)|Japanese article]]) was a nickname given to the Toyota SA due to its small size, as the result of a naming contest the Toyota Company organized in 1947. However, when Toyota eventually entered the American market in 1957 with the Crown, the name was not well received due to connotations of toys and pets.<ref name=America50Toyopet>{{cite web |url=http://www.toyota.com/50th/pdf/toyopet.pdf |title=Toyota's 50th Anniversary in America \u2013 Toyopet |publisher=Toyota |location=US |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910202233/http://www.toyota.com/50th/pdf/toyopet.pdf |archive-date=September 10, 2008}}, retrieved on August 4, 2008.</ref> The name was soon dropped for the American market, but continued in other markets until the mid-1960s.\n\n===1960s\u20131970s===\nBy the early 1960s, the US had begun placing stiff import tariffs on certain vehicles. The so-called \"[[chicken tax]]\" of 1964 placed a 25% tax on imported [[light truck]]s.<ref name=\"wsjtransit\">{{cite news| title = To Outfox the Chicken Tax, Ford Strips Its Own Vans| publisher = The Wall Street Journal, Matthew Dolan, September 22, 2009| url = http://online.wsj.com/article/SB125357990638429655.html| date = September 23, 2009| access-date = September 22, 2009| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090925143145/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB125357990638429655.html| archive-date = September 25, 2009| url-status = live}}</ref> In response to the tariff, Toyota, [[Nissan Motors|Nissan Motor Co.]] and [[Honda|Honda Motor Co.]] began building plants in the US by the early 1980s.<ref name=\"wsjtransit\"/>\n\n===1980s===\n[[File:1987 Toyota Corolla (AE82) CS sedan (2015-11-11) 01.jpg|thumb|By the 1980s [[Toyota Corolla]] was one of the most popular and best selling cars in the world]]\n\nToyota received its first Japanese Quality Control Award at the start of the 1980s and began participating in a wide variety of [[Toyota Motor Corporation#Motorsport history|motorsports]]. Due to the [[1973 oil crisis]], consumers in the lucrative US market began turning to making small cars with better fuel economy. American car manufacturers had considered small economy cars to be an entry-level product, and their small vehicles employed a low level of quality to keep the price low. Conservative Toyota held on to [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-wheel-drive]] designs for longer than most; while a clear first in overall production they were only third in production of front-wheel-drive cars in 1983, behind Nissan and Honda. In part due to this, Nissan's [[Nissan Sunny|Sunny]] managed to squeeze by the Corolla in numbers built that year.<ref name=whp19>{{cite journal | journal = [[Wheels (magazine)|Wheels]] | ref = Wh0684 | title = Japan: Minica magic | first = Yoshi | last = Hattori | page = 19 | date=June 1984 | publisher = Murray Publishers | quote = Nissan built 1,200,000 fwds, Honda about one million, and Toyota 800,000. Mazda was fourth, with 700,000 fwd cars. | location = Sydney, Australia }}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, the Toyota Motor Company and Toyota Motor Sales merged into one company, the Toyota Motor Corporation. Two years later, Toyota entered into a joint venture with General Motors called the New United Motor Manufacturing, Inc, [[NUMMI]], operating an automobile-manufacturing plant in [[Fremont, California|Fremont]], California. The factory was an old General Motors plant that had been closed for two years. It is currently the site of Tesla, Inc.'s assembly plant. Toyota then started to establish new brands at the end of the 1980s, with the launch of their luxury division [[Lexus]] in 1989.\n\n===1990s===\n[[File:Toyota Supra SZ (A80) front.jpg|thumb|Toyota Supra (JZA80) is one of the most recognized Japanese sports cars]]\nIn the 1990s, Toyota began to branch out from producing mostly compact cars by adding many larger and more luxurious vehicles to its lineup, including a full-sized pickup, the [[Toyota T100|T100]] (and later the [[Toyota Tundra|Tundra]]), several lines of SUVs, a sport version of the [[Toyota Camry|Camry]], known as the [[Toyota Solara|Camry Solara]]. They would also launch newer iterations of their sports cars, namely the [[Toyota MR2|MR2]], [[Toyota Celica|Celica]], and [[Toyota Supra|Supra]] during this era.\n\nWith a major presence in Europe, due to the success of [[Toyota Team Europe]], the corporation decided to set up Toyota Motor Europe Marketing and Engineering, [[Toyota Motor Europe|TMME]], to help market vehicles in the continent. Two years later, Toyota set up a base in the United Kingdom, [[TMUK]], as the company's cars had become very popular among British drivers. Bases in [[Indiana]], [[Virginia]], and [[Tianjin]] were also set up. In 1999, the company decided to list itself on the [[New York Stock Exchange|New York]] and [[London Stock Exchange]]s.\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2001, Toyota's [[Toyo Trust and Banking]] merged with two other banks to form [[UFJ Bank]], which was accused of corruption by Japan's government for making bad loans to alleged [[Yakuza]] crime syndicates with executives accused of blocking Financial Service Agency inspections.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/weekly/news/nn2005/nn20050430a4.htm |title=Ex-UFJ execs in scandal avoid prison |work=Japan Times Weekly |location=Japan|date=April 30, 2005 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929131931/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/weekly/news/nn2005/nn20050430a4.htm |archive-date=September 29, 2007}}</ref> The UFJ was listed among [[Fortune Magazine]]'s largest money-losing corporations in the world, with Toyota's chairman serving as a director.<ref>[http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/52/52290.html UFJ Holdings Inc., company profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080129144327/http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/52/52290.html |date=January 29, 2008 }} ''Yahoo Finance''. Retrieved on May 8, 2007.</ref> At the time, the UFJ was one of the largest shareholders of Toyota. As a result of Japan's banking crisis, UFJ merged with the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi to become the [[Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group]].\n\nIn 2002, Toyota managed to enter a [[Formula One]] works team and establish joint ventures with French motoring companies [[Citro\u00ebn]] and [[Peugeot]] a year after Toyota started producing cars in France.\n\nA youth-oriented marque for North America, [[Scion (automobile)|Scion]], was introduced in 2003.\n\nToyota ranked eighth on [[Forbes 2000]] list of the world's leading companies for the year 2005<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/results.jhtml?passListId=18&passYear=2004&passListType=Company&searchParameter1=unset&searchParameter2=unset&resultsStart=1&resultsHowMany=100&resultsSortProperties=%2Bnumberfield1%2C%2Bstringfield2&resultsSortCategoryName=rank&passKeyword=&category1=category&category2=category&fromColumnClick=true|title=Forbes Global 2000|work=Forbes|accessdate=December 27, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060524102554/http://www.forbes.com/lists/results.jhtml?passListId=18&passYear=2004&passListType=Company&searchParameter1=unset&searchParameter2=unset&resultsStart=1&resultsHowMany=100&resultsSortProperties=%2Bnumberfield1,%2Bstringfield2&resultsSortCategoryName=rank&passKeyword=&category1=category&category2=category&fromColumnClick=true|archivedate=May 24, 2006}}</ref> but slid to 55th for 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Toyota Motors|url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/toyota-motor/|work=Forbes|accessdate=June 7, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625141548/http://www.forbes.com/companies/toyota-motor/|archive-date=June 25, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The company was number one in global automobile sales for the first quarter of 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/cars-trucks/daily-news/080424-Toyota-Claims-World-s-Best-Selling-Automaker-Title/|title=Toyota Claims World's Best-Selling Automaker Title|date=April 24, 2008|work=Automotive|publisher=US News|accessdate=December 27, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029033432/http://usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/cars-trucks/daily-news/080424-Toyota-Claims-World-s-Best-Selling-Automaker-Title/|archive-date=October 29, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Toyota released an update of its full-sized truck, the Tundra, produced in two American factories, one in Texas and one in Indiana. ''Motor Trend'' named the Tundra \"Truck of the Year\", and the 2007 [[Toyota Camry]] \"Car of the Year\" for 2007. It also began the construction of two new factories, one to build the [[Toyota RAV4|RAV4]] in Woodstock, Ontario, Canada, and the other to build the [[Toyota Prius]] in Blue Springs, Mississippi, USA. This plant was originally intended to build the [[Toyota Highlander]], but Toyota decided to use the plant in [[Toyota Motor Manufacturing Indiana|Princeton, Indiana, USA]], instead. The company has also found recent success with its smaller models\u2014the Corolla and Yaris.\n\n===2010s===\nIn 2011, Toyota, along with large parts of the Japanese automotive industry, suffered from a series of natural disasters. The [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]] led to a severe disruption of the supplier base and a drop in production and exports.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2011/08/toyotas-financials-hit-by-earthquake| work=Thetruthaboutcars.com| title=Toyota\u2019s Financials Hit By Earthquake| date=August 2, 2011| access-date=May 11, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017120858/http://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2011/08/toyotas-financials-hit-by-earthquake/| archive-date=October 17, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2011/07/this-is-a-tsunami-wave| work=Thetruthaboutcars.com| title=This Is A Tsunami Wave| date=July 29, 2011| access-date=May 11, 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017120457/http://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2011/07/this-is-a-tsunami-wave/| archive-date=October 17, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref> Severe flooding during the 2011 [[monsoon]] season in [[Thailand]] affected Japanese automakers that had chosen Thailand as a production base. Toyota is estimated to have lost production of 150,000 units to the tsunami and production of 240,000 units to the floods.\n\nOn February 10, 2014, it was announced that Toyota would cease manufacturing vehicles and engines in Australia by the end of 2017.<ref name=toyota-exit>{{cite news |last=Dunckley |first=Mathew |url=http://www.portnews.com.au/story/2078487/toyota-confirms-exit-from-australian-manufacturing-in-2017/?cs=2452 |title=Toyota confirms exit from Australian manufacturing in 2017 |work=Port Macquarie News |date=February 10, 2014 |access-date=February 10, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221175235/http://www.portnews.com.au/story/2078487/toyota-confirms-exit-from-australian-manufacturing-in-2017/?cs=2452 |archive-date=February 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=ToyotaExitsAustralianManufacturing>{{cite press release |url=http://www.toyota.com.au/news/toyota-australia-announces-future-plan-for-local-manufacturing |title=Toyota Australia Announces Future Plan For Local Manufacturing |publisher=Toyota |location=Australia |date=February 10, 2014 |access-date=February 10, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222153203/http://www.toyota.com.au/news/toyota-australia-announces-future-plan-for-local-manufacturing |archive-date=February 22, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The decision was based on the unfavourable Australian dollar making exports not viable, the high cost of local manufacture and the high amount of competition in a relatively small local market.<ref name=ToyotaExitsAustralianManufacturing/> The company plans to consolidate its corporate functions in Melbourne by the end of 2017. The head office will remain in Port Melbourne and the Altona plant will be retained for other functions. The workforce is expected to be reduced from 3,900 to 1,300.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.toyota.com.au/news/toyota-australia-announces-its-future-plans |title=Toyota Australia announces its future plans |publisher=Toyota |location=Australia |date=December 3, 2014 |access-date=March 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324100021/http://www.toyota.com.au/news/toyota-australia-announces-its-future-plans |archive-date=March 24, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Both [[Ford Motor Company]] and [[General Motors]] ([[Holden]]) followed suit, ending Australian production in 2016 and 2017 respectively.\n\nThe automaker narrowly topped global sales for the first half of 2014, selling 5.1 million vehicles in the six months ending June 30, 2014, an increase of 3.8% on the same period the previous year. [[Volkswagen AG]], which recorded sales of 5.07 million vehicles, was close behind.<ref name=\"AutoSales\">{{cite news|title=World biggest carmaker tag retained by Toyota|url=http://www.thejapannews.net/index.php/sid/224277905/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/World-biggest-carmaker-tag-retained-by-Toyota|accessdate=July 31, 2014|publisher=The Japan News.Net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808053950/http://www.thejapannews.net/index.php/sid/224277905/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/World-biggest-carmaker-tag-retained-by-Toyota|archive-date=August 8, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Toyota announced it would be cutting its spare-parts prices in China by up to 35%. The company admitted the move was in response to a probe foreshadowed earlier in the month by China's [[National Development and Reform Commission]] of Toyota's Lexus spare-parts policies, as part of an industry-wide investigation into what the Chinese regulator considers exorbitantly high prices being charged by automakers for spare parts and after-sales servicing.<ref name=\"ToyotaChina\">{{cite news|title=Anti-trust probe forces Toyota to cut auto spare parts prices in China|url=http://www.asiapacificstar.com/index.php/sid/224972433|date=August 21, 2014|accessdate=August 22, 2014|publisher=Asia Pacific Star|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826120735/http://www.asiapacificstar.com/index.php/sid/224972433|archive-date=August 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, the company announced that it would invest {{USD|1 billion}} over the next 5 years into [[artificial intelligence]] and robotics research.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Toyota to invest $1 billion into artificial intelligence |url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/11/05/technology/toyota-ai-research/index.html |website=CNNMoney |date=November 5, 2015 |first=Heather |last=Kelly |accessdate=November 10, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109083239/http://money.cnn.com/2015/11/05/technology/toyota-ai-research/index.html |archive-date=November 9, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2016, Toyota invested in [[Uber]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/24/11762420/oyota-uber-partnership-investment-announced |title=Toyota is establishing a 'strategic partnership' with Uber, which is a really big deal |first=Andrew J. |last=Hawkins |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |work=[[The Verge]] |date=May 24, 2016 |access-date=May 25, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805061225/https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/24/11762420/oyota-uber-partnership-investment-announced |archive-date=August 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The invested amount is not public information.\n\nIn March 2016, Toyota partnered with [[Yanmar]] to create a fiberglass pleasure boat using Yanmar outboard marine diesel engines or Toyota inboard engines.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.mynavi.jp/articles/2016/03/10/marin/ |title=\"\u30ac\u30ea\u30d0\u30fc\"\u30e4\u30de\u30cf\u306e\u7259\u57ce\u3092\u5d29\u305b\u308b\u304b!? \u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u3068\u30e4\u30f3\u30de\u30fc\u304c\u30d7\u30ec\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc\u30dc\u30fc\u30c8\u3067\u30bf\u30c3\u30b0 |trans-title=\"Gulliver\" Can you break down the stronghold of Yamaha? Toyota and Yanmar join to make a pleasure boat |work=My Navi |language=ja |date=March 10, 2016 |access-date=August 26, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809213837/http://news.mynavi.jp/articles/2016/03/10/marin/ |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn August 27, 2018, Toyota announced an investment of $500 Million in [[Uber]]'s [[autonomous car]]s.<ref>{{Cite new |url=https://sputniknews.com/business/201808281067524207-toyota-uber-driverless-cars/ |title=Toyota to Invest $500Mln in Uber, Boost Joint Work on Driverless Cars |work=Sputnik International |date=August 28, 2018 |access-date=August 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828095957/https://sputniknews.com/business/201808281067524207-toyota-uber-driverless-cars/ |archive-date=August 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/toyota-to-invest-500-mln-uber-to-develop-driverless-car-wsj-1027487944 |title=Toyota To Invest $500 Mln Uber To Develop Driverless Car: WSJ |work=Business Insider |date=August 27, 2018 |access-date=August 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828134445/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/toyota-to-invest-500-mln-uber-to-develop-driverless-car-wsj-1027487944 |archive-date=August 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Recalls==\n{{Main|2009\u201311 Toyota vehicle recalls}}\nFrom November 2009 through 2010, Toyota recalled more than 9 million cars and trucks worldwide in several [[2009\u20132011 Toyota vehicle recalls|recall campaigns]], and briefly halted production and sales.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/19/business/19toyota.html | work=The New York Times | title=Toyota Pays Its $16.4&nbsp;million Fine Over Pedals | first=Micheline | last=Maynard | date=May 18, 2010 | access-date=February 20, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701094053/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/19/business/19toyota.html | archive-date=July 1, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> After pressure from the NHTSA, Toyota issued the recalls, after reports that several vehicles experienced [[Sudden unintended acceleration|unintended acceleration]].\n\nIn October 2012, Toyota announced a recall of 7.43 million vehicles worldwide to fix malfunctioning power window switches, the largest recall since that of [[Ford Motor Company]] in 1996. The move came after a series of recalls between 2009 and 2011 in which it pulled back around 10 million cars amidst claims of faulty mechanics.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/10/10/uk-toyota-recall-idUKBRE89906B20121010 | title=Toyota to recall 7.4 million vehicles globally on power window glitch | author=Yoko Kubota | work=Reuters | date=October 10, 2012 | access-date=November 16, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028014110/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/10/10/uk-toyota-recall-idUKBRE89906B20121010 | archive-date=October 28, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2014, Toyota agreed to pay a fine of {{USD|1.2 billion}} for concealing information and misleading the public about the safety issues behind the recalls on Toyota and Lexus vehicles affected by unintended acceleration.  Toyota never agreed to be at fault for the problem.\n\nIn early November 2014, Toyota USA enlisted a recall involving defective inflaters and propellant devices that may deploy improperly in the event of a crash, shooting metal fragments into vehicle occupants. More than 7 million vehicles are potentially affected in the United States. This recall only affects vehicles equipped with [[Takata airbag]]s released after the year 2000 in North America. The airbags were manufactured by Takata automotive manufacturing. Toyota is offering a free repair to all affected vehicles worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/massive-takata-airbag-recall-everything-you-need-to-know-including-full-list-of-affected-vehicles |title=Massive Takata Airbag Recall: Everything You Need to Know, Including Full List of Affected Vehicles |first=Clifford |last=Atiyeh |work=Car and Driver |date=November 13, 2014 |accessdate=November 15, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129064936/http://blog.caranddriver.com/massive-takata-airbag-recall-everything-you-need-to-know-including-full-list-of-affected-vehicles/ |archive-date=November 29, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> The fault in the Takata air bags also affected other North American automobile manufacturers as well as European and Japanese automobile manufacturers.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/9-automakers-have-now-issued-recalls-for-dangerous-airbags-nhtsa-still-investigating |title=9 Automakers Have Now Issued Recalls for Dangerous Airbags, NHTSA Still Investigating |work=Car and Driver |first=Clifford |last=Atiyeh |date=July 17, 2014 |accessdate=November 15, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115132022/http://blog.caranddriver.com/9-automakers-have-now-issued-recalls-for-dangerous-airbags-nhtsa-still-investigating/ |archive-date=November 15, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Toyota USA announced a recall of Toyota and Lexus vehicles with Takata airbags that had previously been replaced by the company. The recall affects specific Toyota Corollas, Sequoias, Tundras and Lexus vehicles made between 2002-2005. This recall was announced one year ahead of the initially scheduled recall in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-toyota-takata/toyota-advances-plans-to-replace-takata-airbags-in-65000-vehicles-idUSKBN1OB2IO|title=Toyota advances plans to replace Takata airbags in 65,000 vehicles|last=|first=|date=December 12, 2018|work=Reuters|access-date=December 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212200454/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-toyota-takata/toyota-advances-plans-to-replace-takata-airbags-in-65000-vehicles-idUSKBN1OB2IO|archive-date=December 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Logo and branding==\n[[File:Toyota Sign Development Bertel Schmitt.jpg|thumb|Employee at Toyota Museum explains development of Toyota name and brand]]\n\nIn 1936, Toyota entered the passenger car market with its Model AA and held a competition to establish a new logo emphasizing speed for its new product line. After receiving 27,000 entries, one was selected that additionally resulted in a change of its moniker to \"Toyota\" from the family name \"Toyoda\". The new name was believed to sound better, and its eight-stroke count in the Japanese language was associated with wealth and good fortune. The original logo is no longer found on its vehicles but remains the corporate emblem used in Japan.\n\n[[File:Toyota logo.svg|thumb|left|Toyota wordmark, used as the main logo until 1989 and is currently used as a corporate logo]]\n[[File: Toyota Tacoma TRD Pro P4250811.jpg|thumb|left|[[Toyota Tacoma]] TRD Pro still uses Toyota wordmark]]\n\nStill, no guidelines existed for the use of the brand name, so \"TOYOTA\", which was used throughout most of the world, led to inconsistencies in its worldwide marketing campaigns.\n\nTo remedy this, Toyota introduced a new worldwide logo in October 1989 to commemorate the 50th year of the company, and to differentiate it from the newly released luxury Lexus brand. The logo made its debut on the 1989 Toyota Celsior and quickly gained worldwide recognition. The three ovals in the new logo combine to form the letter \"T\", which stands for Toyota. The overlapping of the two perpendicular ovals inside the larger oval represents the mutually beneficial relationship and trust between the customer and the company while the larger oval surrounding both of these inner ovals represents the \"global expansion of Toyota's technology and unlimited potential for the future\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.toyota.co.jp/en/vision/traditions/nov_dec_04.html |title=Company > Vision & Philosophy > Nov/Dec 2004 |publisher=TOYOTA |accessdate=October 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022095517/http://www2.toyota.co.jp/en/vision/traditions/nov_dec_04.html |archivedate=October 22, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toyota-global.com/showroom/emblem/passion/ |title=Passion &#124; Toyota Motor Corporation Global Website |publisher=Toyota-global.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812024915/http://www.toyota-global.com/showroom/emblem/passion/ |archive-date=August 12, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Toyota AA 1936 - Picture by Bertel Schmitt.jpg|thumb|Hubcap of 1936 Toyota AA, with the old \"Toyoda\" name]]\n\nThe new logo started appearing on all printed material, advertisements, dealer signage, and most of the vehicles themselves in 1990.\n\nIn countries or regions using [[traditional Chinese character]]s, e.g. Hong Kong and Taiwan, Toyota is known as \"\u8c50\u7530\".<ref name=\"Crown Motors\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crown-motors.com/tch/corpinfo/story.aspx|title=Crown Motors Ltd. (Hong Kong) Corporate Information|accessdate=March 19, 2010|year=2010|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217211030/http://www.crown-motors.com/tch/corpinfo/story.aspx|archive-date=February 17, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> In countries using [[simplified Chinese character]]s (e.g. China, Singapore), Toyota is written as \"\u4e30\u7530\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toyota.com.cn/ |title=Toyota China |publisher=Toyota.com.cn |accessdate=September 11, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813233938/http://www.toyota.com.cn/ |archive-date=August 13, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> (pronounced as ''F\u0113ngti\u00e1n'' in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin Chinese]] and ''H\u0254ng Tshan'' in [[Minnanese]]). These are the same characters as the founding family's name \"Toyoda\" in Japanese.\n\n===Japan===\n[[File:Aichi Toyota Moter Headquarter 20160520.jpg|thumb|Toyota Store [[Aichi]] ]]\n[[File:Toyota TOYOPET Japan Car dealership Saitama 1.jpg|thumb|Toyopet Store, [[Saitama, Saitama|Saitama]] ]]\n[[File:Toyota cololla Kyotanabe.JPG|thumb|Corolla Store [[Kyotanabe]] ]]\n[[File:Nets TOYOTA.jpg|thumb|Netz Store, [[Tsurumi-ku, Osaka]] ]]\n{{commons category|Toyota dealerships}}\n\nIn Japan, Toyota currently maintains separate dealership sales channels.<ref name=\"Toyota Japan Dealerships\">{{cite web|title=List of Toyota Dealerships in Japan|url=http://www.toyota-global.com/company/history_of_toyota/75years/data/automotive_business/sales/dealerships/japan/index.html|website=Toyota Japan|publisher=Toyota Motor Corporation|accessdate=January 15, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116060621/http://www.toyota-global.com/company/history_of_toyota/75years/data/automotive_business/sales/dealerships/japan/index.html|archive-date=January 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Toyota sought out to use a [[hierarchical]] marketing approach, similar to methods used in North America, but implemented it at all of its dealership chains, with some models being exclusive to particular locations.\n\nThe first sales channel established in 1946 is called \"Toyota Store\"<ref name = \"Management of Service Businesses in Japan\">{{cite book | last1= Imai | first1= Noriyuki | last2= Matsuo | first2= Takami | last3= Monden | first3= Yasuhiro | year= 2012 | title= Management of Service Businesses in Japan | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=3TR_Z9AbMSsC | location= Singapore | publisher= [[World Scientific]] | page= 42 | isbn= 9789814374668 | access-date= October 27, 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160101190037/https://books.google.com/books?id=3TR_Z9AbMSsC | archive-date= January 1, 2016 | url-status= live }}</ref> (\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u5e97 ''Toyota-ten'') and offers large luxury sedans such as the [[Toyota Century]] and the [[Toyota Crown]].  In more recent years, the Toyota Store's line was expanded to include hybrid and alternate fuel vehicles. In 1955, the \"Toyopet Store\" (\u30c8\u30e8\u30da\u30c3\u30c8\u5e97 ''Toyopetto-ten'') arrived, originally established to sell the [[Toyota Corona]] and the [[Toyota Dyna|Toyopet ToyoAce]] truck, and currently features mid-range models. ([[:ja:\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u81ea\u52d5\u8eca\u65e5\u672c\u56fd\u5185\u8ca9\u58f2\u7db2\u5e74\u8868|Toyota's five channel dealerships in Japan chronology]] in Japanese.)\n\nThe \"Toyota Publica Store\" (\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30d1\u30d6\u30ea\u30ab\u5e97 ''Toyota Paburika-ten'') was established in 1961 to sell the [[Toyota Publica]]. In 1966 it was renamed the \"Toyota Corolla Store\" (\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30ab\u30ed\u30fc\u30e9\u5e97 ''Toyota Kar\u014dra-ten'') to sell the [[Toyota Corolla]].<ref name=\"Toyota Japan Dealerships\"/> The dealership chain focuses on budget models.\n\nThe \"Toyota Auto Store\" (\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30aa\u30fc\u30c8\u5e97 ''Toyota \u014cto-ten'') sales network was established in 1967 to sell the Corolla companion, the [[Toyota Sprinter]], and was renamed \"Netz Toyota Store\" in 1998.<ref name=\"Toyota Japan Dealerships\"/> The \"Vista\" name was used on a new Camry-clone, called the [[Toyota Vista]]. The Toyota Vista network was replaced with two networks; \"Netz Toyota\" (\u30cd\u30c3\u30c4\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u5e97 ''Nettsu-Toyota-ten'') in August 1998, and Lexus in 2004. Some former Vista models were rebranded as [[Lexus]] (\u30ec\u30af\u30b5\u30b9 ''Rekusasu''), such as the Altezza and the Aristo, while other products have been taken over by the \"Netz Toyota\", which was already selling the [[Toyota ist]] and the [[Toyota RAV4]]. \"Netz\" is an acronym for \"Network of Energetic Teams for Zenith\", and targets young buyers.\n\nToyota previously operated a commercial dealership called [[:ja:\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30c7\u30a3\u30fc\u30bc\u30eb\u5e97|Toyota Diesel Shop]] (\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30c7\u30a3\u30fc\u30bc\u30eb\u5e97 ''Toyota D\u012bzeru-ten'') from 1957 until 1988 that sold various commercial platform trucks, buses, and forklifts, such as the [[Toyota Dyna]] and the [[Toyota Coaster]]. [[Hino Motors|Hino]] products were sold at specific Hino locations and shared at Toyota Diesel Store locations after Toyota acquired the company in 1967. Starting in 1980, the Diesel Shop also sold the Starlet, Corolla, Corona, Vista, and Crown installed with diesel engines. When the Toyota Diesel Store was disbanded, commercial products were divided between Toyota Store and Toyopet Store locations.\n\nIn 2012, selected Japanese dealership locations were given a special designation called \"Area 86\" that resembled the North American Toyota network, called [[Scion (automobile)|Scion]], to sell the [[Toyota 86]], building on the marketing approach started with [[WiLL]] branded products.<ref name=\"Toyota Japan Dealerships\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=JAPAN: Area 86 will be first stop for Toyota coupe buyers|url=https://www.just-auto.com/news/area-86-will-be-first-stop-for-toyota-coupe-buyers_id121292.aspx|website=Just Auto|publisher=Aroq Ltd|accessdate=September 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921001123/https://www.just-auto.com/news/area-86-will-be-first-stop-for-toyota-coupe-buyers_id121292.aspx|archive-date=September 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 2017, the \"Area 86\" network was rebranded as \"GR\" for [[Toyota Gazoo Racing WRT|Gazoo Racing]], sharing a similar approach to the performance division [[Toyota Racing Development]] or \"TRD\", providing various upgrades for the 86, Vitz, Prius, Mark X, Harrier, Noah and Voxy.<ref name=\"Toyota Gazoo Racing\">{{cite web|title=Toyota Gazoo Racing|url=https://toyotagazooracing.com/our-story/|website=Toyota Gazoo Racing|publisher=Toyota Motor Corporation|accessdate=September 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920063003/http://toyotagazooracing.com/our-story/|archive-date=September 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the female idol group, [[AKB48]], Toyota and AKS, has worked together to create a subunit named 'Team 8'. Team 8 is created with the idea, 'Idols who come to meet you'. They have a total of 47 members, each representing a prefecture of Japan.\n\n{{anchor|Toyota Store (Japan)}}\n;Vehicles sold at [[:ja:\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u5e97|Toyota Store]]\n\nThe following is a list of all past and present models and where they were available at retail channels nationally. Most models were exclusive to particular retail chains, while some models, like the Prius, are available at all sales channels.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toyota.jp/service/dealer/spt/search-addr?mode=form&SELECT_MODEL_KIND=1&CAR_NAME_EN=ALLION&SEARCH_DETAIL_FLG=1&padid=ag341_from_alli_top_rec_dealer |title=\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf \u8ca9\u58f2\u5e97 {{!}} \u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u81ea\u52d5\u8ecaWEB\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 |trans-title=Toyota dealer {{!}} Toyota Motor web site |publisher=Toyota |location=Japan |access-date=July 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511094306/http://toyota.jp/service/dealer/spt/search-addr?mode=form&SELECT_MODEL_KIND=1&CAR_NAME_EN=ALLION&SEARCH_DETAIL_FLG=1&padid=ag341_from_alli_top_rec_dealer |archive-date=May 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Retail chains in Tokyo, Osaka and [[Okinawa]] are different.<ref name=\"Toyota Japan Dealerships\"/>\n\n[[File:Toyota-Dealer-Toyota.png]]\n\n[[Toyota Century|Century]], [[Toyota Crown Majesta|Crown Majesta]], [[Toyota Crown|Crown]], [[Toyopet Master|Master]], [[Toyota Sai|SAI]], [[Toyota Mirai|Mirai]], [[Toyota Prius|Prius]], [[Toyota Prius c|Aqua]], [[Toyota Allion|Allion]], [[Toyota Succeed|Succeed]], [[Toyota Blade|Blade]], [[Toyota Avensis|Avensis]], [[Toyota Sienta|Sienta]], [[Toyota Corolla RunX|Corolla RunX]], [[Toyota C-HR|C-HR]], [[Toyota Porte|Porte]], [[Toyota Estima|Estima]], [[Toyota Isis|Isis]], [[Toyota Roomy|Roomy]], [[Toyota FJ Cruiser|FJ Cruiser]], [[Toyota Comfort|Comfort]], [[Toyota Land Cruiser|Land Cruiser]], [[Toyota Hilux Surf|Hilux Surf]], [[Toyota Land Cruiser Prado|Land Cruiser Prado]], [[Toyota Dyna|Dyna]], [[Toyota Stout|Stout]], [[Toyota Esquire|Esquire]], [[Toyota Coaster|Coaster]], [[Toyota QuickDelivery|QuickDelivery]], [[Toyota 2000GT|2000GT]], [[Toyota Carina|Carina]], [[Toyota Carina ED|Carina ED]], [[Toyota 86|GT-86]], [[Toyota Brevis|Brevis]], [[Toyota Gaia|Gaia]], [[Toyota Cavalier|Cavalier]], [[Toyota Classic|Classic]], [[Toyota MasterAce|MasterAce]], [[Toyota Hilux|Hilux]], [[Toyota Mega Cruiser|Mega Cruiser]], [[Toyota Soarer|Soarer]], [[Toyota Origin|Origin]], [[Toyota Caldina|Caldina]].\n\n{{anchor|Toyopet Store (Japan)}}\n;Vehicles sold at [[:ja:\u30c8\u30e8\u30da\u30c3\u30c8\u5e97|Toyopet Store]]\n\n[[File:Toyota-Dealer-Toyopet.png]]\n\n[[Toyota Mark X|Mark X]], [[Toyota Sai|SAI]], [[Toyota Mirai|Mirai]], [[Toyota Premio|Premio]], [[Toyota Prius|Prius]], [[Toyota Prius c|Aqua]], [[Toyota Belta|Belta]], [[Toyota Mark X ZiO|Mark X ZiO]], [[Toyota Succeed|Succeed]], [[Toyota Ractis|Ractis]], [[Toyota Auris|Auris]], [[Toyota Blade|Blade]], [[Toyota 86|GT-86]], [[Toyota Porte|Porte]], [[Toyota Harrier|Harrier]], [[Toyota Vanguard|Vanguard]], [[Toyota Esquire|Esquire]], [[Toyota Rush|Rush]], [[Toyota C-HR|C-HR]], [[Toyota Avensis|Avensis]], [[Toyota Alphard|Alphard]], [[Toyota Comfort|Comfort]], [[Toyota Hiace|HiAce]], [[Toyota Toyoace|ToyoAce]], [[Toyota Tank|Tank]], [[Toyota Sienta|Sienta]], [[Toyota Pixis Space|Pixis Space]], [[Toyota Mark II|Mark II-Mark II Qualis-Mark II Blit]], [[Toyota Corona|Corona]], [[Toyota Corona EXiV|Corona EXiV]], [[Toyota Corona#T160|Corona Coupe]], [[Toyota Corsa|Corsa]], [[Toyota Opa|Opa]], [[Toyota Avalon|Avalon]], [[Toyota Progr\u00e8s|Progr\u00e8s]], [[Toyota Cami|Cami]], [[Toyota ist|ist]], [[Toyota Platz|Platz]], [[Toyota Soarer|Soarer]], [[Toyota Hilux|Hilux]], [[Toyota Cynos|Cynos]], [[Toyota Regius|Regius]], [[Toyota Celsior|Celsior]], [[Toyota Origin|Origin]], [[Toyota Caldina|Caldina]], [[Toyota Ipsum|Ipsum]].\n\n{{anchor|Toyota Corolla Store (Japan)}}\n{{anchor|Toyota Publica Store (Japan)}}\n;Vehicles sold at [[:ja:\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30ab\u30ed\u30fc\u30e9\u5e97|Toyota Corolla Store]] (starting 1966), formerly Toyota Publica Store\n\n[[File:Toyota-Dealer-Corolla.png]]\n\n[[Toyota Sai|SAI]], [[Toyota Camry|Camry]], [[Toyota Prius|Prius]], [[Toyota Prius c|Aqua]], [[Toyota Corolla Axio|Corolla Axio]], [[Toyota 86|GT-86]], [[Toyota Belta|Belta]], [[Toyota Spade|Spade]], [[Toyota Probox|Probox]], [[Toyota Corolla Rumion|Corolla Rumion]], [[Toyota C-HR|C-HR]], [[Toyota Ractis|Ractis]], [[Toyota Passo|Passo]], [[Toyota Corolla Verso|Corolla Verso]], [[Toyota Sera|Sera]], [[Toyota Vanguard|Vanguard]], [[Toyota Roomy|Roomy]], [[Toyota Estima|Estima]], [[Toyota Noah|Noah]], [[Toyota Avensis|Avensis]], [[Toyota Sienta|Sienta]], [[Toyota TownAce|TownAce]], [[Toyota Pixis|Pixis]], [[Toyota Publica|Publica]], [[Toyota Tercel|Tercel]], [[Toyota Windom|Windom]], [[Toyota Scepter|Scepter]], [[Toyota Corolla Ceres|Corolla Ceres]], [[Toyota Origin|Origin]], [[Toyota Ipsum|Nadia]], [[Toyota WiLL|WiLL]], [[Toyota RAV4|RAV4]], [[Toyota Sports 800|Sports 800]], [[Toyota Celica|Celica]], [[Toyota Supra|Supra]], [[Toyota AE86|Corolla Levin]], [[Toyota Celica XX|Celica XX]], [[Toyota Celica Camry|Celica Camry]].\n\n{{anchor|Toyota Netz Store (Japan)}}\n{{anchor|Toyota Vista Store (Japan)}}\n{{anchor|Toyota Auto Store (Japan)}}\n;Vehicles sold at [[:ja:\u30cd\u30c3\u30c4\u5e97|Netz Store]] (starting 1998), formerly [[:ja:\u30c8\u30e8\u30bf\u30d3\u30b9\u30bf\u5e97|Toyota Vista Store]] (starting 1980), formerly Toyota Auto Store (starting 1967)\n\n[[File:Toyota-Dealer-Netz.png]]\n\n[[Toyota Vitz|Vitz]], [[Toyota Sai|SAI]], [[Toyota Prius|Prius]], [[Toyota Prius c|Aqua]], [[Toyota ist|ist]], [[Toyota Auris|Auris]], [[Toyota bB|bB]], [[Toyota Avensis|Avensis]], [[Toyota Raum|Raum]], [[Toyota Spade|Spade]], [[Toyota Wish|Wish]], [[Toyota Voxy|Voxy]], [[Toyota RAV4|RAV4]], [[Toyota C-HR|C-HR]], [[Toyota Kluger|Kluger]], [[Toyota Vellfire|Vellfire]], [[Toyota iQ|iQ]], [[Toyota Allex|Allex]], [[Toyota Tank|Tank]], [[Toyota Pixis|Pixis]], [[Toyota Fun Cargo|Fun Cargo]], [[Toyota Pronard|Pronard]], [[Toyota Altezza|Altezza]], [[Toyota Verossa|Verossa]], [[Toyota Curren|Curren]], [[Toyota Aristo|Aristo]], [[Toyota MR-S|MR-S]], [[Toyota MR2|MR2]], [[Toyota Starlet|Starlet]], [[Toyota Vista|Vista]], [[Toyota Cresta|Cresta]], [[Toyota Sprinter|Sprinter]], [[Toyota Voltz|Voltz]], [[Toyota Blizzard|Blizzard]], [[Toyota Chaser|Chaser]], [[Toyota Sprinter Marino|Sprinter Marino]], [[Toyota Carib|Carib]], [[Toyota Granvia|Granvia]], [[Toyota AE86|Sprinter Trueno]], [[Toyota LiteAce|LiteAce]], [[Toyota Ipsum|Ipsum]], [[Toyota 86|GT-86]], [[WiLL]] (1999\u20132004).\n\n===Toyota slogans===\n====Australia====\n\n* ''See How Much Car Your Money Can Buy'' (1979-1980)\n* ''Something Special For You.'' (1981-1983)\n\n* ''Oh What a feeling!'' (1983\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.adnews.com.au/adnews/toyota-feeling-it-for-30-years |title=Toyota feeling it for 30 years |first=Paul |last=McIntyre |work=AdNews |location=Australia |date=July 12, 2013 |access-date=February 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190225223555/http://www.adnews.com.au/adnews/toyota-feeling-it-for-30-years |archive-date=February 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Bangladesh====\n* ''Running Towards'' (1974\u20131979)\n* ''Leads awa