ant Governor of New York]]: [[Stan Lundine]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Carolina]]: [[Robert B. Jordan, III]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until month and day unknown), [[James Carson Gardner]]  ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting month and day unknown)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Dakota]]: [[Lloyd Omdahl]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Ohio]]: [[Paul R. Leonard]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Oklahoma]]: [[Robert S. Kerr III]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Pennsylvania]]: [[Mark Singel]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Rhode Island]]: [[Richard A. Licht]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until month and day unknown), [[Roger N. Begin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting month and day unknown)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Carolina]]: [[Nick Theodore]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Dakota]]: [[Walter Dale Miller]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Tennessee]]: [[John S. Wilder]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]: [[William P. Hobby, Jr.]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Utah]]: [[W. Val Oveson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Vermont]]: [[Howard Dean]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Virginia]]: [[Douglas Wilder]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]]: [[John Cherberg]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 11), [[Joel Pritchard]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 11)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Wisconsin]]: [[Scott McCallum]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n}}\n|}\n\n==Events==\n\n===January===\n[[File:George H. W. Bush, President of the United States, 1989 official portrait (cropped).jpg|thumb|120px|[[January 20]]: [[George H. W. Bush]] becomes President]]\n* January 1 &ndash; The [[Canada\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement]] comes into effect.\n* January 4 &ndash; Second [[Gulf of Sidra incident (1989)|Gulf of Sidra incident]]: Two [[Libya]]n [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-23|MiG-23 \"Floggers\"]] are engaged and shot down by two [[US Navy]] [[F-14 Tomcat]]s.\n* January 10 &ndash; [[Harris Trust and Savings Bank]] of [[Chicago]] settles a government enforcement action by agreeing to pay $14 million in backpay to women and minorities, the largest such settlement ever obtained from a single employer.\n* January 11\n** [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] delivers his farewell address to the nation.\n** The [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] adopts Proposition 42, which withdraws athletic scholarships from athletes who fail to meet minimal academic standards.\n* January 12 &ndash; [[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]] [[George H. W. Bush]] announces the final members of his [[Cabinet of the United States|cabinet]], naming [[James D. Watkins]] as [[United States Secretary of Energy|Secretary of Energy]] and [[William Bennett]] as the first director of the [[Office of National Drug Control Policy]].\n* January 13 &ndash; [[Bernhard Goetz]] is sentenced to one year in prison and fined $5,000 for shooting four young men on the New York subway in 1984.\n* January 16 &ndash; A Hispanic [[Miami]] police officer shoots and kills a speeding black motorcyclist in the [[Overtown (Miami)|Overtown]] section of Miami, Florida, starting three days of rioting.\n* January 17 &ndash; [[Stockton massacre]]: Patrick Edward Purdy kills five children, wounds 30 and then shoots himself in [[Stockton, California]].\n* January 18 &ndash; The [[Republican National Committee]] elects [[Lee Atwater]] as its chairman.\n* January 20 \u2013 [[George H. W. Bush]] is sworn in as the 41st [[President of the United States]].\n* January 22 &ndash; The [[San Francisco 49ers]] defeat the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] in [[Super Bowl XXIII]].\n* January 24 \n**Serial killer [[Theodore Bundy]] is executed in [[Florida]]'s [[electric chair]].\n**[[Joel Steinberg]] is convicted of manslaughter in the beating death of a 6-year-old child he was raising.\n* January 31 &ndash; [[Northway, Alaska|Northway]], [[Alaska]] records the highest mean sea level pressure on record in the United States with a reading of 31.85 [[inch of mercury|inHg]] (1078.6 [[millibar]]s)<ref>[http://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/world-and-us-anticyclonic-high-barometric-pressure-records World and US High Barometric Pressure records] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014082056/http://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/world-and-us-anticyclonic-high-barometric-pressure-records |date=2014-10-14 }}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* February 7 \n**The [[Los Angeles, California]] City Council bans the sale or possession of semiautomatic weapons.\n**The [[101st United States Congress]] rejects a proposed 51 percent pay raise for its members, federal judges, and certain other high-ranking government officials.\n* February 10\n**[[Ron Brown (U.S. politician)|Ron Brown]] is elected chairman of the [[Democratic National Committee]], becoming the first [[African American]] to lead a major United States [[political party]].\n** President Bush meets with [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Brian Mulroney]] in [[Ottawa]], laying the groundwork for the [[Air Quality Agreement|Acid Rain Treaty of 1991]].\n* February 11 &ndash; [[Barbara Harris (bishop)|Barbara Harris]] is the first woman consecrated as a bishop of the [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America]].\n* February 14 &ndash; The first of 24 [[Global Positioning System]] [[satellite]]s is placed into orbit.\n* February 23 &ndash; After protracted testimony, the U.S. [[Senate Armed Services Committee]] rejects, 11\u20139, President Bush's nomination of [[John Tower]] for Secretary of Defense.\n* February 23&ndash;27 &ndash; U.S. President Bush visits [[Japan]], [[China]], and [[South Korea]], attending the funeral of [[Hirohito]] and then meeting with China's [[Deng Xiaoping]] and South Korea's [[Roh Tae-woo]].\n* February 26 &ndash; ''[[60 Minutes]]'' airs a report claiming that [[apple]]s sprayed with [[Daminozide|Alar]] may cause cancer in children, leading many schools to remove apples from their cafeterias.\n\n===March===\n[[File:EVOSWEB 013 oiled bird3.jpg|thumb|120px|March 24: [[Exxon Valdez oil spill]]]]\n* March &ndash; The unemployment rate drops to a low of 5.0%, the lowest since December 1973.\n* March 1\n** The [[Berne Convention for the Protection of Literary and Artistic Works|Berne Convention]], an international [[treaty]] on [[copyright]]s, is ratified by the United States.\n** [[Louis Wade Sullivan]] starts his term of office as [[U.S. Secretary of Health and Human Services]].\n** [[James D. Watkins]] starts his term of office as [[U.S. Secretary of Energy]].\n* March 3 &ndash; Former [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[Robert McFarlane]] is fined $20,000 and given two years' probation for misleading Congress about the [[Iran\u2013Contra affair]].\n* March 4\n**[[TIME|Time, Inc]]. and [[Warner Communications]] announce plans for a merger, forming [[Time Warner]].\n**[[Eastern Air Lines]] machinists and baggage workers walk off the job to protest pay cuts. The airline subsequently filed for bankruptcy protection five days later, on March 9.\n* March 9 &ndash; By a vote of 53 to 47, the [[United States Senate|Senate]] votes to reject the nomination of [[John Tower]] as [[United States Secretary of Defense]].  President Bush subsequently nominated [[Dick Cheney]] the next day, and Cheney was confirmed and sworn in as defense secretary on March 17.\n* March 13 &ndash; A [[geomagnetic storm]] causes the collapse of the Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec power grid. 6 million people are [[power outage|left without power]] for 9 hours. Some areas in the northeastern U.S. and in Sweden also lose power, and [[aurora (astronomy)|aurora]]e are seen as far as [[Texas]].\n* March 13\u201317 &ndash; The [[Food and Drug Administration]] bans the import of [[grape]]s from [[Chile]] after traces of [[cyanide]] are found in two grapes.\n* March 13\u201318 &ndash; The [[Space Shuttle Discovery|Space Shuttle ''Discovery'']] flies mission [[STS-29]].\n* March 14 &ndash; [[Gun control]]: U.S. President [[George H. W. Bush]] bans the importation of certain guns deemed [[assault weapons]] into the United States.\n* [[March 20]] &ndash; [[Dick Cheney]] is sworn in as the new [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]], succeeding [[Frank Carlucci]].{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n* March 22\n** Congress passes a bill to protect the job of whistle blowers who expose government waste or fraud.\n** [[National Football League]] commissioner [[Pete Rozelle]], commissioner since 1960, announces he will step down when a replacement is found.\n** [[Clint Malarchuk]] of the [[National Hockey League|NHL]] [[Buffalo Sabres]] suffers an almost fatal injury when another player accidentally slits his throat.\n* March 23 &ndash; [[Stanley Pons]] and [[Martin Fleischmann]] announce that they have achieved [[cold fusion]] at the [[University of Utah]].\n* March 24 &ndash; [[Exxon Valdez oil spill]]: In [[Alaska]]'s [[Prince William Sound]] the ''[[Exxon Valdez]]'' spills {{convert|240000|oilbbl|m3}} of [[Petroleum|oil]] after running aground.\n* March 29 &ndash; The [[61st Academy Awards]] are held at the [[Shrine Auditorium]] in [[Los Angeles, California]], with ''[[Rain Man]]'' winning [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]].\n\n===April===\n* April 1 &ndash; [[Bill White (first baseman)|Bill White]] becomes president of baseball's [[National League]], becoming the first [[African American]] to head a major sports league.\n* April 3\n**The [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball]] team defeats the [[Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball]] team to win the [[1989 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]]. \n**[[Richard M. Daley]] is elected [[Mayor of Chicago]].\n* April 5 &ndash; Beginning of the [[Pittston Coal strike]] after miners had worked 14 months without a contract.\n* April 9 &ndash; More than 300,000 demonstrators march in [[Washington, D.C.]] in support of legal [[abortion in the United States]].\n* April 14 &ndash; The U.S. government seizes the Irving, California [[Lincoln Savings and Loan Association]]; [[Charles Keating]] (for whom the [[Keating Five]] were named \u2013 [[John McCain]] among them) eventually goes to jail, as part of the massive 1980s [[Savings and Loan Crisis]] which costs U.S. taxpayers nearly $200 billion in bailouts, and many people their life savings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/24/business/judge-rejects-keating-suit-sees-looting-of-lincoln.html|title=Judge Rejects Keating Suit; Sees 'Looting' of Lincoln|first1=Stephen|last1=Labaton|first2=Special to The New York|last2=Times|date=24 August 1990|publisher=|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n* April 17 &ndash; The [[House Committee on Standards of Official Conduct]] charges [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Jim Wright]] with improperly evading limits on outside income and accepting improper gifts.\n* April 19\n** [[Trisha Meili]] is attacked while jogging in [[New York City]]'s [[Central Park]]; as her identity remains secret for years, she becomes known as the \"Central Park Jogger.\"\n** A gun turret explodes on the U.S. battleship [[USS Iowa (BB-61)|''Iowa'']], killing 47 crew members.\n* April 20 &ndash; [[NATO]] debates modernizing short range missiles; although the U.S. and [[United Kingdom|U.K.]] are in favor, [[West German]] Chancellor [[Helmut Kohl]] obtains a concession deferring a decision.\n\n===May===\n* May 1 &ndash; [[Disney's Hollywood Studios|Disney-MGM Studios]] at [[Walt Disney World]] opens to the public for the first time.\n* May 4\n** In the trial of [[Oliver North]] on charges related to the [[Iran\u2013Contra affair]], the jury finds North guilty of three criminal charges and not guilty of nine.\n** [[STS-30]] was launched, deploying the [[Venus]]-bound ''[[Magellan (spacecraft)|Magellan]]'' probe.\n* May 8 &ndash; [[STS-30]] lands at [[Edwards Air Force Base]] in [[California]] after four days of its mission and the successful deployment of a Venus spacecraft.\n* May 12 &ndash; A [[Southern Pacific Railroad]] freight train [[San Bernardino train disaster|crashes on Duffy Street]] in [[San Bernardino, California]].\n* May 15-25 &ndash; [[Los Angeles]] schoolteachers go on strike. The strike ends with the teachers gaining more administrative control and a 24% pay raise.\n* May 19 &ndash; The [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] closes above 2,500 for the first time since  [[Black Monday (1987)]].\n* May 25 &ndash; Thirteen days after a Southern Pacific train derails, a Calnev pipeline explodes at the same section of Duffy Street in San Bernardino, California.\n* May 26 &ndash; United States House of Representatives Majority Whip [[Tony Coelho]] resigns from the [[United States House of Representatives]], saying he wants to spare his family from an investigation into his finances.\n* May 31 &ndash; [[Jim Wright]] announces his resignation as Speaker of the House of Representatives.\n\n===June===\n* June 4 &ndash; ''[[Jerome Robbins' Broadway]]'' wins the [[Tony Award for Best Musical]] and five other Tonys.\n* June 6 &ndash; The [[United States House of Representatives]] elects [[Tom Foley]] as its new speaker.\n* June 12 &ndash; The [[Corcoran Gallery of Art]] removes [[Robert Mapplethorpe]]'s gay photography exhibition.\n* June 13\n**The [[Detroit Pistons]] beat the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] to win the [[1989 NBA Finals]].\n**President Bush vetoes a minimum-wage bill passed by Congress on May 17 that would have increased the minimum wage to $4.55 an hour.\n* June 14 &ndash; A [[Titan IV]] blasts off from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]].\n* June 21 &ndash; In ''[[Texas v. Johnson]]'', the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruled that burning the [[Flag of the United States]] was protected speech under the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution]].\n* June 23 &ndash; The film ''[[Batman (1989 film)|Batman]]'' opens, earning more than $40 million in its first weekend, a [[United States box office records|box office record]].\n* June 23-24 &ndash; Three shipping accidents in a 12-hour period create [[oil spill]]s in [[Rhode Island]], [[Delaware]], and [[Texas]].\n* June 24 &ndash; In ''[[Penry v. Lynaugh]]'', the Supreme Court rules that states can execute murderers as young as 16 or who are [[Mental retardation|mentally retarded]].\n* June 27 &ndash; A federal appeals court overturns the February 1988 conviction of [[Lyn Nofziger]] for illegal lobbying.\n\n===July===\n* July 3 &ndash; In ''[[Webster v. Reproductive Health Services]]'', the Supreme Court gives the states new authority to restrict abortions.\n* July 5\n** The television show ''[[Seinfeld]]'' premieres.\n** Oliver North is fined $150,00, and given a two-year suspended sentence and three years probation and ordered to perform 1,200 hours of community service for his crimes in the Iran-contra affair.\n* July 9\u201312 &ndash; U.S. President [[George H. W. Bush]] travels to Poland and Hungary, pushing for U.S. economic aid and investment.\n* July 17 &ndash; Maiden flight of the [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit|B-2 stealth bomber]].\n* July 18 &ndash; Actress [[Rebecca Schaeffer]] is murdered by an obsessed fan, leading to stricter stalking laws in California.\n* July 19 &ndash; [[United Airlines Flight 232]] ([[Douglas DC-10]]) crashes in [[Sioux City, Iowa]], killing 112; 184 on board survive.\n* July 21 &ndash; The [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] closes above 2,600 for the first time since [[Black Monday (1987)]].\n* July 26 &ndash; A federal [[grand jury]] indicts [[Cornell University]] student [[Robert Tappan Morris, Jr.]] for releasing a [[computer virus]], making him the first person to be prosecuted under the 1986 [[Computer Fraud and Abuse Act]].\n*July 31 &ndash; [[Nintendo]]'s [[Game Boy]] is released in North America. \n\n===August===\n* August 5 &ndash; Congress passes the [[Financial Institutions Reform, Recovery, and Enforcement Act of 1989]], which is signed into law by President Bush on August 9. The act provides a $166-billion bailout to failed savings and loans and overhauls regulation of the industry.\n* August 7 \n**U.S. Representative [[Mickey Leland]] (D-TX) and 15 others die in a plane crash in [[Ethiopia]].\n**[[FedEx|Federal Express]] purchases [[Flying Tiger Line]] for approximately 800 million U.S. dollars.\n* August 8 &ndash; [[STS-28]]: [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']] takes off on a secret 5-day military mission.\n* August 10 &ndash; President Bush nominates [[United States Army]] Gen. [[Colin Powell]] as [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], making him the first African American to hold that position.\n* August 16&ndash;17 &ndash; [[Woodstock '89]] festival.\n* August 20 &ndash; In [[Beverly Hills, California]], [[Lyle and Erik Menendez]] shoot their wealthy parents to death in the family's den.\n* August 22 &ndash; [[Nolan Ryan]] becomes the first [[pitcher]] in the history of [[Major League Baseball]] to get 5,000 [[strikeout]]s.\n* August 23 &ndash; [[Yusef Hawkins]] is shot in the [[Bensonhurst]] section of [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], sparking racial tensions between [[African American]]s and [[Italian American]]s.\n* August 24\n**Record-setting [[baseball]] player [[Pete Rose]] agrees to a lifetime ban from the sport following allegations of illegal gambling, thereby preventing his induction into the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]].\n**The Dow Jones Industrial Average ends the day at 2,734.64, its highest closing since Black Monday (1987).\n* August 27 &ndash; A [[Delta II]] rocket owned by [[McDonnell Douglas]] launches a [[communications satellite|television satellite]], the first time a privately owned rocket had orbited a payload.\n* August 29 &ndash; Harry Zych, a diver and salvager, files a lawsuit to gain ownership of the wreck of the [[PS Lady Elgin|''Lady Elgin'']] which he has recently discovered in Lake Michigan in [[Highland Park, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://openjurist.org/941/f2d/525/zych-v-unidentified-wrecked-and-abandoned-vessel-believed-to-be-the-seabird|title=941 F2d 525 Zych v. Unidentified Wrecked and Abandoned Vessel Believed to Be the \"Seabird\"|first1=United States Court of|last1=Appeals|first2=Seventh|last2=Circuit|date=21 August 1991|publisher=|volume=F2d|issue=941|pages=525|via=openjurist.org}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n* September 1 &ndash; [[Commissioner of Baseball]] [[A. Bartlett Giamatti]] dies of a [[heart attack]].  On September 13, club owners elect [[Fay Vincent]] as his successor.\n* September 2-3 &ndash; [[Fraternity]] members attending the Greekfest fraternity festival in [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]] spend two days in rioting and looting.\n* September 5 &ndash; U.S. President [[George H. W. Bush]] holds up a bag of [[cocaine]] purchased across the street at [[President's Park#Lafayette Park|Lafayette Park]], and proposes to spend $7.9 billion in the [[War on Drugs]], in his first televised speech to the nation.\n* September 8 &ndash; Former president [[Ronald Reagan]] undergoes surgery to remove fluid on his brain. He recovers quickly.\n* September 14 &ndash; [[Standard Gravure shooting]]: Factory worker Joseph Wesbecker kills 8 and injures 12 before committing suicide inside a factory in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].\n* September 21 &ndash; [[Hurricane Hugo]] makes landfall in [[South Carolina]], causing $7 billion in damage.\n* September 27&ndash;28 &ndash; President Bush and the governors of the 50 U.S. states meet at the [[University of Virginia]] to discuss education policy.\n* September 28 &ndash; [[Braniff (1983\u20131990)|Braniff Incorporated]] files for bankruptcy for the second time since 1982.\n* September 29 &ndash; In the biggest narcotics seizure on record, drug agents confiscate 21.4 short tons of [[cocaine]] and more than $12 million in cash from a [[Los Angeles]] warehouse.\n\n===October===\n[[File:Cypress structure.jpeg|thumb|120px|October 17: [[Loma Prieta earthquake]]]]\n[[Image:Galileo Deployment (high res).jpg|right|thumb|upright|120px|October 18: ''Galileo'' and its Inertial Upper Stage (IUS) booster being deployed by the [[Space Shuttle Atlantis|Space Shuttle ''Atlantis'']] on the [[STS-34]] mission.]]\n* October 4 &ndash; More than 55,000 [[Boeing]] machinists go on strike. They return to work on November 22 after winning higher pay.\n* October 5 &ndash; A jury in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] convicts [[televangelist]] [[Jim Bakker]] of fraud and conspiracy. On October 24, he is sentenced to 45 years in prison and fined $500,000.\n* October 9 &ndash; The Dow Jones Industrial Average closes at a record high of 2,791.41.\n* October 12 &ndash; Congress passes the [[Flag Protection Act]] of 1989, which Bush allows to become law without his signature on October 28.\n* October 13 &ndash; [[Friday the 13th mini-crash]]: The [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] plunges 190.58 points, or 6.91 percent, to close at 2,569.26, most likely after the [[junk bond]] market collapses.\n* October 15 &ndash; [[Wayne Gretzky]] becomes the leading scorer in the history of the [[National Hockey League]].\n* October 17 &ndash; The 6.9 {{M|w|link=y}} [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake|Loma Prieta earthquake]] shakes the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] and the [[Central Coast (California)|Central Coast]] with a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale|Mercalli intensity]] of IX (''Violent''). Sixty-three people were killed and damage amounted to $5.6\u20136 billion.\n* October 18 &ndash; [[STS-34]] is launched, deploying the [[Jupiter]]-bound ''[[Galileo (spacecraft)|Galileo]]'' probe.\n* October 19 &ndash; The [[Wonders of Life]] pavilion opens at [[Epcot]] in [[Walt Disney World]], [[Florida]].\n* October 20\n** The Senate convicts Judge [[Alcee Hastings]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Florida]] of perjury and conspiracy to obtain a bribe, and removes him from office.\n** A federal jury in [[New York City]] convicts Rep. [[Robert Garcia (New York politician)|Robert Garc\u00eda]] of extortion and conspiracy.\n* October 23\n** The [[Phillips Disaster]] in [[Pasadena, Texas]] kills 23 and injures 314 others.\n** [[STS-34]] lands at [[Edwards Air Force Base]] in [[California]] after five days of its mission and the successful deployment of a Jupiter-bound spacecraft.\n** Congress fails to override Bush's veto of a bill that would have restored funding for abortions for poor women who were the victims of rape or incest.\n* October 26 &ndash; [[National Football League|NFL]] owners elect [[Paul Tagliabue]] as NFL commissioner.\n* October 28 &ndash; The [[Oakland Athletics]] beat the [[San Francisco Giants]] to win the [[1989 World Series]].\n\n===November===\n* November 2 &ndash; [[North Dakota]] and [[South Dakota]] celebrate their 100th birthdays.\n* November 3 &ndash; The Senate convicts Judge [[Walter Nixon]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Mississippi]] of lying under oath to a federal grand jury and removes him from office.\n* November 7 \n**[[Douglas Wilder]] wins the [[Virginia]] governor's race, becoming the first elected [[African American]] governor in the United States.\n**[[David Dinkins]] becomes the first [[African American]] mayor of [[New York City]].\n* November 8 &ndash; Congress passes legislation to raise the minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.25 an hour by April 1991. Bush signs this bill on November 17.\n* November 9 &ndash; The [[Berlin Wall]] is brought down.\n* November 15 &ndash; [[Lech Walesa]], leader of [[Poland]]'s [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity movement]], addresses a [[Joint session of the United States Congress]].\n* November 15&ndash;16 &ndash; [[November 1989 tornado outbreak]]: [[Tornado]]es in the [[Eastern United States]] kill at least 31 people.\n* November 16\n** Six [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] priests\u2014among them [[Ignacio Ellacur\u00eda]], [[Segundo Montes]], and [[Ignacio Mart\u00edn-Bar\u00f3]]\u2014their housekeeper, and her teenage daughter, are murdered by [[Western Hemisphere Institute for Security Cooperation|U.S. trained]] [[Military of El Salvador|Salvadoran soldiers]].\n** The House of Representatives passes amendments to strengthen the [[Ethics in Government Act]] of 1978; the Senate passes its own amendments the next day.\n* November 19 &ndash; [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] Soccer Team qualified to the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]] after 40 years of absences, beating [[Trinidad and Tobago|Trinidad & Tobago]] 1-0 in Port Spain, The goal scored by [[Paul Caligiuri]] was named as:[[Shot heard round the world (soccer)|Shot heard round the world]]\n* November 21 &ndash; [[North Carolina]] celebrates its [[1789|bicentennial]] statehood.\n* November 22\n** Congress repeals the [[Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act]] of 1988.\n** The [[Space Shuttle Discovery|Space Shuttle ''Discovery'']] begins [[STS-33]].\n\n===December===\n[[Image:Panama clashes 1989.JPEG|thumb|120px|December 20: [[United States invasion of Panama]]]]\n* December 2 &ndash; The ''[[Solar Maximum Mission]]'' research satellite, launched in 1980, crashes back to earth.\n* December 3 &ndash; [[Cold War]]: In a [[Malta Summit|meeting]] off the coast of [[Malta]], U.S. President [[George H. W. Bush]] and Soviet leader [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] release statements indicating that the [[Cold War]] between their nations may be coming to an end.\n* December 7 &ndash; A Miami, Fla. jury convicts police officer William Lozano for the January 16 deaths of a black motorcyclist and his passenger.\n* December 12 &ndash; Hotelier [[Leona Helmsley]] is sentenced to four years in prison and fined $7.2 million for tax evasion.\n* December 16&ndash;18 &ndash; Mail bombings kill a federal judge in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] and a lawyer in [[Savannah, Georgia]].\n* December 17 &ndash; The television show ''[[The Simpsons]]'' premiers on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]].\n* December 20 &ndash; ''[[United States invasion of Panama|Operation Just Cause]]'' is launched in an attempt to overthrow [[Panama]]nian dictator [[Manuel Noriega]].\n\n===Ongoing===\n* [[Cold War]] (1947\u20131991)\n\n==Births==\n* January 3 [[Alex D. Linz]], actor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/alexander_david_linz_born_1989_19298133|title=Alexander David Linz, Born 01/03/1989 in California {{!}} CaliforniaBirthIndex.org|website=www.californiabirthindex.org|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> \n* January 4\n** [[Sessilee Lopez]], model\n**[[Kevin Pillar]], baseball player\n**[[Graham Rahal]], race car driver\n* January 6 \n** [[James Durbin (singer)|James Durbin]], singer\n** [[Derrick Morgan (American football)|Derrick Morgan]], American football player\n* January 10\n** [[Conor Dwyer]], Olympic swimmer\n** [[Emily Meade]], actress\n* January 13 &ndash; [[Beau Mirchoff]], American-Canadian actor\n* January 15\n** [[Keiffer Hubbell]], ice dancer\n** [[Tasha Reign]], pornographic actress, nude model, stripper, producer, and sex columnist\n* January 17 &ndash; [[Kelly Marie Tran]], actress\n* January 22 &ndash; [[Nick Simmons]], actor and singer\n* January 30 \n** [[Jahvid Best]], American football player\n** [[Khleo Thomas]], actor and rapper\n* February 8  \n** [[JaJuan Johnson]], basketball player\n** [[Julio Jones]], football player\n* February 13 &ndash; [[Katie Volding]], actress\n* February 15 &ndash; [[Bonnie Dennison]], actress\n* February 16 &ndash; [[Elizabeth Olsen]], actress\n* February 17 &ndash; [[Chord Overstreet]], actor and singer\n* February 21\n** [[Corbin Bleu]], actor, model, dancer, film producer and singer-songwriter\n** [[Kristin Herrera]], actress\n** [[Scout Taylor-Compton]], actress\n* February 23 \n** [[Evan Bates]], ice dancer\n** [[Chris Conte]], American football player\n* February 24 &ndash; [[Kosta Koufos]], basketball player\n* February 27 &ndash; [[Stefano Langone]], singer\n* March 1 &ndash; [[Sonya Kitchell]], singer-songwriter\n* March 22 &ndash; [[Tyler Oakley]], [[YouTube]] and podcast personality\n* March 26 &ndash; [[Von Miller]], American football player\n* April 28 &ndash; [[Stephen Ettinger]], mountain biker\n* May 10 &ndash; [[Lindsey Shaw]], actress\n* May 22 &ndash; [[Trevor Reckling]], baseball player\n* May 29 &ndash; [[Riley Keough]], actress\n* May 31 \n** [[Lauren Barnes]], soccer player\n** [[Noah Gundersen]], singer-songwriter and guitarist \n* June 2 \n** [[Freddy Adu]], Ghanaian-American soccer player\n** [[Michael Dunigan]], basketball player\n* June 7 &ndash; [[Ashley Melnick]], model, [[Miss Texas|Miss Texas 2010]]\n* June 9 &ndash; [[Logan Browning]], actress\n* June 13 &ndash; [[Lisa Tucker (singer)|Lisa Tucker]], singer, musical theater and television actress\n* June 14 &ndash; [[Lucy Hale]], actress and singer\n* June 20 \n** [[Christopher Mintz-Plasse]], actor\n** [[Terrelle Pryor]], American football player\n* June 27 &ndash; [[Kimiko Glenn]], actress and singer\n* June 28 &ndash; [[Markiplier]], [[YouTube]] personality\n* July 2\n** [[Dev (singer)|Dev]] (Devin Tailes), pop singer-songwriter\n** [[Alex Morgan]], soccer player\n* July 3 &ndash; [[Elle King]], singer-songwriter and actress\n* July 4 &ndash; [[Alyssa Miller]], model\n* July 5 &ndash; [[Sean O'Pry]], model\n* July 14 &ndash; [[Rolando McClain]], American football player\n* July 16 &ndash; [[Carlito Olivero]], singer\n* July 21 \n** [[Chelsie Hightower]], dancer and choreographer\n** [[Jasmine Cephas Jones]], actress\n** [[Rory Culkin]], actor\n** [[Narcissa Wright]], speedrunner\n* July 23\n** [[K. J. Wright]], American football player\n** [[Donald Young (tennis)|Donald Young]], tennis player\n* July 25 &ndash; [[Andrew Caldwell (actor)|Andrew Caldwell]], actor\n* July 29 \n** [[Marlen Esparza]], boxer<ref>{{cite web|title=Marlen Esparza|url=https://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/ES/Marlen-Esparza.aspx|website=Team USA|accessdate=24 April 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n** [[Hona Costello]], singer\n** [[Jake Smollett]], actor\n* July 31\n** [[Alexis Knapp]], actress and singer\n** [[Jessica Williams (actress)|Jessica Williams]], actress\n** [[Zelda Williams]], actress\n* August 5 &ndash; [[Jessica Nigri]], model and actress\n* August 8\n** [[Ken Baumann]], actor and author\n** [[Anthony Rizzo]], baseball player\n* August 9\n** [[Meredith Deane]], actress\n** [[Jason Heyward]], American baseball player\n* August 18 &ndash; [[Anna Akana]], actress, filmmaker, author, and comedian\n* August 21 &ndash; [[Hayden Panettiere]], actress, singer and model\n* September 5 &ndash; [[Kat Graham]], Swiss-born actress, singer, dancer, and model\n* September 21 &ndash; [[Jason Derulo]], singer\n* October 1 &ndash; [[Brie Larson]], actress and singer\n* October 2 &ndash; [[Brad Peltz]], ice hockey player\n* October 4 \n** [[Dakota Johnson]], actress and model\n** [[Lil Mama]], rapper\n** [[Kimmie Meissner]], figure skater\n** [[Rich Homie Quan]], rapper\n* October 13 &ndash; [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]], politician\n* October 15 &ndash; [[Tucker Reed]], Blogger, author, journalist and feminist activist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inmate.jacksoncounty.org/Inmate.aspx?SheriffOfficeNumber=00136278&BookingNumber=1871372|title=Inmate|website=inmate.jacksoncounty.org}}</ref>\n* October 16 &ndash; [[Jack Salvatore Jr.]], production assistant and actor\n* October 25 &ndash; [[Marina Keegan]], author and journalist\n* October 30 &ndash; [[Nastia Liukin]], artistic gymnast\n* November 6\n** [[Jozy Altidore]], soccer player\n** [[Aaron Hernandez]], American football player (d. [[2017]])\n* November 14\n**[[T. Y. Hilton]], American football player\n**[[The Ready Set]], singer-songwriter\n* November 22 \n** [[Alden Ehrenreich]], actor\n** [[Candice Glover]], singer and actress\n* November 24 &ndash; [[Jordan Witzigreuter]], singer-songwriter\n* December 12 &ndash; [[Mike Glennon]], American football player\n* December 13 &ndash; [[Taylor Alison Swift]], singer-songwriter\n* December 18 &ndash; [[Ashley Benson]], actress\n* December 21 &ndash; [[Mark Ingram Jr.]], American football player\n* December 22 &ndash; [[Jordin Sparks]], singer-songwriter and actress\n\n==Deaths==\n* February 18 &ndash; [[Mildred Burke]], American wrestler and trainer (b. [[1915 in the United States|1915]])\n* April 22 &ndash; [[Henry R. Paige]], Marine Corps general (b. [[1904 in the United States|1904]])\n* April 26 &ndash; [[Lucille Ball]], film and television actress and model (b. [[1911 in the United States|1911]])\n* May 30 &ndash; [[Claude Pepper]], United States Senator from Florida from 1936 till 1951. (b. [[1900 in the United States|1900]])\n* July 10 &ndash; [[Mel Blanc]], voice actor, actor, radio comedian, and recording artist (b. [[1908 in the United States|1908]])\n* October 6 &ndash; [[Bette Davis]], film and television actress (b. [[1908 in the United States|1908]])\n* October 25 &ndash; [[Mary McCarthy (author)|Mary McCarthy]], novelist, critic and political activist (b. [[1912 in the United States|1912]])\n* November 5 &ndash; [[Vladimir Horowitz]], Ukrainian-born American classical pianist and composer (b. 1903)\n\n==See also==\n* [[1989 in American television]]\n* [[List of American films of 1989]]\n* [[Timeline of United States history (1970\u20131989)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{US year nav}}\n{{Timeline of United States history}}\n{{North America topic|1989 in}}\n\n[[Category:1989 in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:1989 by country]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRonald Brown(link changed toRon Brown) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Baltic people in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{external links|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group    = Baltic British\n|image =  \n|caption =\n|population  = '''Baltic-born residents'''<br>108,711 Lithuanian-born (2011 census)<br>61,441 Latvian-born (2011 census)\n|popplace = [[London]], [[Birmingham]], [[Manchester]], [[Liverpool]], [[Kingston upon Hull]], [[York]] and [[Glasgow]]\n|langs    = [[English language|English]], [[Latvian language|Latvian]], [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]], [[Russian language|Russian]].\n|rels = [[Christianity]]{{\u00b7}}[[Judaism]]{{*}}[[Protestantism]]\n|related-c = [[Balts]]\n}} \n'''Baltic people in the United Kingdom''' are those born or raised in the UK, or residents, who are of ethnically [[Balts|Baltic]], meaning [[Latvians|Latvian]] or [[Lithuanians|Lithuanian]], origin.\n\n==History, population and settlement==\nIn the early 20th century, many [[Latvia]]n and [[Lithuania]]n refugees began to settle in Glasgow and at its height in the 1950s, there were around 10,000 in the Glasgow area.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,,1692714,00.html| title=Lithuanians in Glasgow|date=2006-01-23| author=The Guardian| accessdate=2007-07-09}}</ref>\n\nSignificant numbers of Baltic people moved to the UK in 1947 under a government backed scheme called ''Westward Ho''. The first group of [[displaced persons]] (DPs) from the British zone of occupation of Germany arrived in the UK in 1947, called the ''Balt Cygnets''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OmHMultyyy0C&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq=Westward+Ho+baltic+cygnets#v=onepage&q=Westward%20Ho%20baltic%20cygnets&f=false|chapter=On the Significance of Being White: European Migrant Workers in the British Economy in the 1940s and 2000s|title=New Geographies of Race and Racism|isbn=978-0-7546-7085-8|first=Linda|last=McDowell|editor1-last=Dwyer|editor1-first=Claire|editor2-last=Bressey|editor2-first=Caroline|year=2008|location=Aldershot|publisher=Ashgate|pages=51\u201364}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2011 UK Census]] recorded 95,730 Lithuanian-born residents in [[England]], 1,353 in [[Wales]],<ref name=EngWal2011>{{2011CensusEngWalCoB|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> 4,287 in [[Scotland]],<ref name=Scot2011>{{2011CensusScotlandCoB|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> and 7,341 in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref name=NI2011>{{2011CensusNICoB|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> The census recorded 53,977 Latvian-born residents in England, 692 in Wales,<ref name=EngWal2011/> 4,475 in Scotland,<ref name=Scot2011/> and 2,297 in Northern Ireland.<ref name=NI2011/> \n\nThe previous, [[2001 UK Census]], had recorded 4,363 UK residents born in Lithuania and 4,275 born in Latvia.<ref name=\"Census2001\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.oecd.org/dataoecd/18/23/34792376.xls|title=Country-of-birth database|publisher=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|accessdate=26 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504031258/http://www.oecd.org/dataoecd/18/23/34792376.xls|archive-date=4 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Lithuanians in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Burrell, Kathy and Panayi, Panikos: ''Histories and Memories: Latvians and Their History in Britain'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=KK0GR2ZrVL4C&pg=PA89&lpg=PA89&dq=%22Lithuanians+in+Britain%22&source=web&ots=oZbl4pS0tc&sig=S_XsRo2Mg6xOywx_JJZYt3Ryo8s&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result]\n* Budriuniene, Jolanta: ''Regeneration of the Lithuanian Emigrant Press: Fifteen Years' Experience'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20090520230527/http://www.kirmus.ee/baltic_archives_abroad_2006/kogumik/eng/Budriuniene_eng.pdf]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080516174541/http://www.hyperbia.co.uk/baltic.html The Baltic Music information centre UK]\n*[http://www.labrit.co.uk/vispareja-informacija-latviesiem-no-latvijas/  Latvians in Britain]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/LatviesuNacionalaPadome Latvian National Council]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080724184427/http://www.labrit.co.uk/koris.html London Latvian Choir]\n*[http://www.dvmaja.com Latvian Welfare Fund/Daugavas Vanagu Fonds]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080513085835/http://www.draudze.org.uk/majas.htm  United London Latvian Church]\n*[http://www.uklietuvis.com Uklietuvis.com - Website for UK Lithuanians]\n*[https://www.lvchamber.uk LVChamber.uk - Latvian Chamber of Commerce for the United Kingdom]\n*[https://www.lccuk.co.uk LCCUK.co.uk - Lithuanian Chamber of Commerce in the United Kingdom]\n{{EuropeansinUK}}\n{{Latvian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Baltic states]]\n[[Category:British people of Lithuanian descent| ]]\n[[Category:British people of Latvian descent| ]]\n[[Category:British people of Estonian descent| ]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian diaspora in Europe]]\n[[Category:Latvian diaspora]]\n[[Category:Immigration to the United Kingdom by country of origin]]\n", "text_old": "{{external links|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group    = Baltic British\n|image =  \n|caption =\n|population  = '''Baltic-born residents'''<br>108,711 Lithuanian-born (2011 census)<br>61,441 Latvian-born (2011 census)\n|popplace = [[London]], [[Birmingham]], [[Manchester]], [[Liverpool]], [[Kingston upon Hull]], [[York]] and [[Glasgow]]\n|langs    = [[English language|English]], [[Latvian language|Latvian]], [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]], [[Russian language|Russian]].\n|rels = [[Christianity]]{{\u00b7}}[[Judaism]]{{*}}[[Protestantism]]\n|related-c = [[Balts]]\n}} \n'''Baltic people in the United Kingdom''' are those born or raised in the UK, or residents, who are of ethnically [[Balts|Baltic]], meaning [[Latvians|Latvian]] or [[Lithuanians|Lithuanian]], origin.\n\n==History, population and settlement==\nIn the early 20th century, many [[Latvia]]n and [[Lithuania]]n refugees began to settle in Glasgow and at its height in the 1950s, there were around 10,000 in the Glasgow area.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,,1692714,00.html| title=Lithuanians in Glasgow|date=2006-01-23| author=The Guardian| accessdate=2007-07-09}}</ref>\n\nSignificant numbers of Baltic people moved to the UK in 1947 under a government backed scheme called ''Westward Ho''. The first group of [[displaced persons]] (DPs) from the British zone of occupation of Germany arrived in the UK in 1947, called the ''Balt Cygnets''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OmHMultyyy0C&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq=Westward+Ho+baltic+cygnets#v=onepage&q=Westward%20Ho%20baltic%20cygnets&f=false|chapter=On the Significance of Being White: European Migrant Workers in the British Economy in the 1940s and 2000s|title=New Geographies of Race and Racism|isbn=978-0-7546-7085-8|first=Linda|last=McDowell|editor1-last=Dwyer|editor1-first=Claire|editor2-last=Bressey|editor2-first=Caroline|year=2008|location=Aldershot|publisher=Ashgate|pages=51\u201364}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2011 UK Census]] recorded 95,730 Lithuanian-born residents in [[England]], 1,353 in [[Wales]],<ref name=EngWal2011>{{2011CensusEngWalCoB|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> 4,287 in [[Scotland]],<ref name=Scot2011>{{2011CensusScotlandCoB|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> and 7,341 in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref name=NI2011>{{2011CensusNICoB|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> The census recorded 53,977 Latvian-born residents in England, 692 in Wales,<ref name=EngWal2011/> 4,475 in Scotland,<ref name=Scot2011/> and 2,297 in Northern Ireland.<ref name=NI2011/> \n\nThe previous, [[2001 UK Census]], had recorded 4,363 UK residents born in Lithuania and 4,275 born in Latvia<ref name=\"Census2001\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.oecd.org/dataoecd/18/23/34792376.xls|title=Country-of-birth database|publisher=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|accessdate=26 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504031258/http://www.oecd.org/dataoecd/18/23/34792376.xls|archive-date=4 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Lithuanians in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Burrell, Kathy and Panayi, Panikos: ''Histories and Memories: Latvians and Their History in Britain'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=KK0GR2ZrVL4C&pg=PA89&lpg=PA89&dq=%22Lithuanians+in+Britain%22&source=web&ots=oZbl4pS0tc&sig=S_XsRo2Mg6xOywx_JJZYt3Ryo8s&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result]\n* Budriuniene, Jolanta: ''Regeneration of the Lithuanian Emigrant Press: Fifteen Years' Experience'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20090520230527/http://www.kirmus.ee/baltic_archives_abroad_2006/kogumik/eng/Budriuniene_eng.pdf]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080516174541/http://www.hyperbia.co.uk/baltic.html The Baltic Music information centre UK]\n*[http://www.labrit.co.uk/vispareja-informacija-latviesiem-no-latvijas/  Latvians in Britain]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/LatviesuNacionalaPadome Latvian National Council]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080724184427/http://www.labrit.co.uk/koris.html London Latvian Choir]\n*[http://www.dvmaja.com Latvian Welfare Fund/Daugavas Vanagu Fonds]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080513085835/http://www.draudze.org.uk/majas.htm  United London Latvian Church]\n*[http://www.uklietuvis.com Uklietuvis.com - Website for UK Lithuanians]\n*[https://www.lvchamber.uk LVChamber.uk - Latvian Chamber of Commerce for the United Kingdom]\n*[https://www.lccuk.co.uk LCCUK.co.uk - Lithuanian Chamber of Commerce in the United Kingdom]\n{{EuropeansinUK}}\n{{Latvian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Baltic states]]\n[[Category:British people of Lithuanian descent| ]]\n[[Category:British people of Latvian descent| ]]\n[[Category:British people of Estonian descent| ]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian diaspora in Europe]]\n[[Category:Latvian diaspora]]\n[[Category:Immigration to the United Kingdom by country of origin]]\n", "name_user": "Alpha Centauri 5932", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory, population an