ww.fijitimes.com/shoppers-buying-in-bulk/|title=Shoppers buying in bulk|website=FijiTimes|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319160140/https://www.fijitimes.com/shoppers-buying-in-bulk/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* The Ministry of Education cancelled the Coca-Cola Games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/sports/athletics/coca-cola-games-cancelled/|title=Coca Cola Games cancelled|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319212236/https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/sports/athletics/coca-cola-games-cancelled/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* The [[Fiji Rugby Union]] (FRU) had suspended all forms of rugby competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijione.tv/news-posts/all-forms-of-rugby-cancelled/|title=ALL FORMS OF RUGBY CANCELLED|website=FIJI TV|language=en-US|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320192753/https://www.fijione.tv/news-posts/all-forms-of-rugby-cancelled/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Reserve Bank of Fiji]] reduced its overnight policy rate (OPR) to 0.25 percent from 0.50 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fijisun.com.fj/2020/03/18/covid-19-reserve-bank-reduce-overnight-policy-rate/|title=COVID-19: Reserve Bank Reduce Overnight Policy Rate|language=en-US|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318204609/https://fijisun.com.fj/2020/03/18/covid-19-reserve-bank-reduce-overnight-policy-rate/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Tourism in Fiji|Tourism Fiji]] says consumer confidence in travel is currently really low.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijivillage.com/news/Consumer-confidence-in-travel-is-currently-really-low---Tourism-Fiji-r58f4x/|title=Consumer confidence in travel is currently really low - Tourism Fiji|last=Fijivillage|website=www.fijivillage.com|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320192804/https://www.fijivillage.com/news/Consumer-confidence-in-travel-is-currently-really-low---Tourism-Fiji-r58f4x/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Reserve Bank of Fiji forecast the domestic economy to fall into a recession after almost a decade of economic growth.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fijitimes.com/fijis-central-bank-forecasts-recession-in-domestic-economy/ |title=Fiji\u2019s central bank forecasts recession in domestic economy |website=The Fiji Times |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n* The [[Fiji Indian organisations|TISI Sangam Convention]] had cancelled the 2020 annual event.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fijivillage.com/news/TISI-Sangam-cancels-2020-Annual-TISI-Sangam-Convention-due-to-COVID-19-845fxr/ |title=TISI Sangam cancels 2020 Annual TISI Sangam Convention due to COVID-19 |website=www.fijivillage.com |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321024332/https://www.fijivillage.com/news/TISI-Sangam-cancels-2020-Annual-TISI-Sangam-Convention-due-to-COVID-19-845fxr/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Fiji Football Association|Fiji Football]] had postponed all its scheduled matches, meetings and workshops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijitimes.com/fiji-fa-calls-off-matches-events/|title=Fiji FA calls off matches, events|website=The Fiji Times|access-date=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322061146/https://www.fijitimes.com/fiji-fa-calls-off-matches-events/|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Construction Industry seeing a downturn where raw materials are running out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/construction-industry-seeing-a-downturn-due-to-covid-19/|title=Construction Industry seeing a downturn due to COVID-19|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n*Nurses facing unprecedented physical and psychological challenges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/nurses-can-face-unprecedented-mental-challenges/|title=Nurses can face unprecedented mental challenges|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Fiji|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Fiji]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania|Fiji]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Fiji]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Fiji\n| map1            = \n| places          = \n| legend1         = \n| alt1            = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Fiji]]\n| first_case      = [[Lautoka]]\n| arrival_date    = {{start date|2020|3|19|df=yes}}<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=19|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 15\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 0\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [http://www.health.gov.fj/Portal/press-release/ Health.gov.fj]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was reported to have spread to [[Fiji]] on 19 March 2020. A total of 15 cases have been confirmed as of 7 April 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" /> From 19 March, COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Fiji medical cases chart}}\n\n=== February 2020 ===\nOn 3 February, the [[Politics of Fiji|Government of Fiji]] toughened border security. Borders were closed to foreign nationals who have been in mainland China within 14 days of their intended travel to Fiji.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/fiji-to-close-boarders-to-foreign-nationals-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=Fiji toughens on border entry amidst coronavirus concerns |website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202191732/https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/fiji-to-close-boarders-to-foreign-nationals-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak/ |archive-date=2 February 2020 |access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref> Measures to maintain a hygienic environment and screening ill passengers will continue to be taken in-flight to further minimise any risk.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fijivillage.com/news/Fijis-borders-closed-to-all-foreign-nationals-who-have-been-in-China-within-14-days-of-their-travel-to-Fiji-5s29rk/ |title=Fiji's borders closed to all foreign nationals who have been in China within 14 days of their travel to Fiji |last=Limited |first=Communications Fiji |website=fijivillage.com |access-date=19 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309152939/https://fijivillage.com/news/Fijis-borders-closed-to-all-foreign-nationals-who-have-been-in-China-within-14-days-of-their-travel-to-Fiji-5s29rk/ |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, Fiji extended its travel ban and announced that travellers from [[Italy]], [[Iran]] and the [[South Korea]]n cities of [[Daegu]] and [[Cheongdo County|Cheongdo]] would be denied entry. From 28 February, all cruise ships entering Fiji have been required to make first berths at ports in [[Suva]] and [[Lautoka]], where passengers undergo medical and travel history checks.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=https://amp.rnz.co.nz/article/d796c6bb-8ea3-408f-9b64-a9a17609b4b9 |title=Coronavirus: Fiji extends travel ban amid growing concerns |website=amp.rnz.co.nz |access-date=27 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228185231/https://amp.rnz.co.nz/article/d796c6bb-8ea3-408f-9b64-a9a17609b4b9 |archive-date=28 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 15 March, Prime Minister [[Frank Bainimarama]] had announced that from 16 March cruise ships will be banned from berthing anywhere in Fiji and international events will not be allowed in Fiji. Government ministers and staff will be restricted from travelling overseas.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/pm-announces-new-covid-19-measures-including-ban-on-ships-and-visitors/ |title=PM announces new COVID-19 measures, including ban on cruise ships |website=fbcnews.com.fj |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319014915/https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/pm-announces-new-covid-19-measures-including-ban-on-ships-and-visitors/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Fiji confirmed its first case, a 27 year old Fijian citizen who is a flight attendant of [[Fiji Airways]]. He had arrived from [[San Francisco]] returning via [[Nadi]] on 16 March. On 17 March, he had travelled from Nadi to [[Auckland]] and a return from Auckland to Nadi on the same day. He was admitted to [[Health in Fiji|Lautoka Hospital.]] <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fijivillage.com/news/COVID-19-patient-is-a-27-year-old-flight-attendant-who-had-recent-travel-history-to-USA-and-NZ---Dr-Sahukhan-4x8rf5/ |title=COVID-19 patient is a 27-year-old flight attendant who had recent travel history to USA and NZ - Dr. Sahukhan |work=[[Fiji Village]] |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320024938/https://www.fijivillage.com/news/COVID-19-patient-is-a-27-year-old-flight-attendant-who-had-recent-travel-history-to-USA-and-NZ---Dr-Sahukhan-4x8rf5/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prime Minister Frank Bainimarama announced a further extension of the ban to foreign nationals who have been present in the [[United States]], as well as all of [[Europe]] including the [[United Kingdom]]. Also all travellers arriving in or returning to Fiji from outside of the country must self-isolate for 14 days.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/pm-announces-major-restrictions-including-closure-of-some-services-due-to-covid-19/|title=PM announces major restrictions including closure of some services due to COVID-19|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319163738/https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/pm-announces-major-restrictions-including-closure-of-some-services-due-to-covid-19/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Prime Minister Voreqe Bainimarama press conference.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Voreqe Bainimarama's press conference regarding COVID-19]]\n\nOn 20 March, all schools and non-essential businesses in Lautoka had been closed at midnight, however banks, supermarkets, pharmacies and essential businesses remained open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijitimes.com/covid-19-fiji-widens-existing-travel-restrictions-to-include-spain/|title=COVID-19: Fiji widens existing travel restrictions to include Spain|website=FijiTimes|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318135907/https://www.fijitimes.com/covid-19-fiji-widens-existing-travel-restrictions-to-include-spain/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijitimes.com/covid-19-lautoka-schools-closed-until-further-notice/|title=COVID-19: Lautoka schools closed until further notice|website=FijiTimes|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319150350/https://www.fijitimes.com/covid-19-lautoka-schools-closed-until-further-notice/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Minister for Education, Heritage and Arts [[Rosy Akbar]] in consultation with the [[Prime Minister of Fiji|Prime Minister]] announced that the national term one school holidays that was initially scheduled from 20 April to 1 May will be brought forward to 23 March to 3 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/first-term-school-holidays-brought-forward/|title=First term school holidays brought forward|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320192748/https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/first-term-school-holidays-brought-forward/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Fiji Airways had suspended all international flights until the end of May, with the exception of twice-weekly services between [[Singapore]] and Nadi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fiji-airways-suspends-flights-implements-leave-without-pay/|title=Fiji Airways suspends flights, implements leave without pay|last=N|first=Edwin|last2=FBCNews|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320192750/https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fiji-airways-suspends-flights-implements-leave-without-pay/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government had established two fever clinics in Lautoka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijitimes.com/covid-19-fever-clinics-set-up-in-lautoka/|title=COVID-19: Fever clinics set up in Lautoka|website=FijiTimes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320212957/https://www.fijitimes.com/covid-19-fever-clinics-set-up-in-lautoka/|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Fiji confirmed its second case, it was the first local transmission case through household contact. She is the mother of the first patient and is admitted in [[Health in Fiji|Nadi Hospital]]. Other family members are in quarantine and being monitored.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/fiji-second-covid-19-cases-recorded/|title=Fiji's second COVID-19 case recorded|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-03-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321033747/https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/fiji-second-covid-19-cases-recorded/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Fiji confirmed its third case, a one-year-old nephew of the first patient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/fijis-third-covid-19-case-confirmed/|title=Toddler is Fiji's third COVID-19 patient|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The government established eight fever clinics around the country with six clinics running in [[Nasinu]], [[Labasa]], [[Savusavu]], and Nabouwalu.Two others have been running in Lautoka since 20 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/eight-fever-clinics-now-open/|title=Eight fever clinics now open|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, Fiji confirmed its fourth case, a 28-year-old Fijian citizen, who had returned from [[Sydney]] over the weekend and is not related to the first three cases. He and his immediate family members are in quarantine and being monitored at the [[Health in Fiji|Navua Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fijis-fourth-covid-19-case-confirmed/|title=Fiji's fourth COVID-19 case confirmed|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>  Fiji Airways had suspended all Singapore and [[Hong Kong]] flights after the two countries introduced its border restrictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fiji-suspends-all-singapore-and-hong-kong-flights/|title=Fiji suspends all Singapore and Hong Kong flights|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, Fiji confirmed its fifth case, a 31-year-old Fijian citizen from Lautoka. She was in contact with the first case, the flight attendant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fijis-fifth-covid-19-case-confirmed-in-lautoka/|title=Fiji's fifth COVID-19 case confirmed in Lautoka|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Prime Minister Frank Bainimarama had announced that [[Nadi International Airport]] will shut down from 26 March and all local shipping services will cease from 29 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/nadi-airport-to-close-shipping-services-end-sunday/|title=Nadi Airport to close, shipping services end Sunday|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, Attorney General and Minister for Economy [[Aiyaz Sayed-Khaiyum]] revealed the COVID-19 response [[Economy of Fiji|budget]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412772/covid-19-fiji-govt-unveils-us400m-stimulus-package|title=Covid-19: Fiji govt unveils $US400m stimulus package|website=Radio NZ|date=27 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Prime Minister Frank Bainimarama announced a nationwide curfew from 10 p.m. to 5 a.m. that would take effect on 30 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijitimes.com/nationwide-curfew-to-come-into-effect-from-sunday/|title=COVID-19: Nationwide curfew to come into effect from Monday|website=The Fiji Times|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Minister for Education, Heritage and Arts Rosy Akbar announced that the school holidays will be extended for another two weeks until 17 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/school-holidays-extended-another-two-weeks/|title=School holidays extended for another two weeks|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 1 April, Minister for Heath and Medical Services [[Ifereimi Waqainabete]] announced that the Lautoka lock down will be extended till 7 April to ensure that no COVID-19 cases left undetected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/123123lautoka-lockdown-extended/|title=Lautoka lockdown extended to Tuesday|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Fiji confirmed two cases, a Fijian couple from Suva. Prime Minister Frank Bainimarama stated that the sixth case is a 21-year-old woman and the seventh case is her 33-year-old husband. They are in admitted at Navua Hospital. Due to this, the Prime Minister announced that Suva will be going into a lockdown effective from 3 April at 5 a.m. Also, the government renewed the national curfew where it will start from 8 p.m. to 5 a.m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fiji-confirms-latest-cases-of-covid-19/|title=Fiji confirms latest cases of COVID-19, Suva in lockdown from tomorrow|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, Fiji confirmed five cases from Labasa, Suva, Nadi and Lautoka. Two cases was confirmed in Labasa, a 54-year-old man who is the ninth case, he is related to the sixth and seventh case and is admitted at [[Health in Fiji|Labasa Hospital]]. The ninth case had arrived from [[India]] via Singapore on the 22 March. He had failed to isolate for 14 days, thus increasing the risk of community transmission in Fiji. It is believed that he contracted the disease while attending the [[2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|Tablighi Jamaat]] in India. An eighth case was confirmed in Suva, a 11-year-old female who contracted the disease from her parents, the sixth and seventh cases. She is admitted at Navua Hospital. A tenth case was confirmed in Lautoka, a 39-year-old female from Natowaqa. She is in admitted at Lautoka Hospital. An eleventh case was confirmed in Nadi, a 20-year-old Fijian from Nadovi with travel history to Auckland, New Zealand. The twelfth case was confirmed in Labasa, the 25-year-old daughter-in-law of the ninth case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/five-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-total-up-to-12/|title=Five more test positive for COVID-19, total up to 12|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/12-covid-19-cases-in-fiji/|title=11-year-old amongst new confirmed COVID-19 cases|last=N|first=Edwin|last2=FBCNews|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Fiji confirmed two cases from Labasa and Lautoka. In Labasa, the wife of the ninth case who contracted the disease from him. She was taken into isolation two days before being diagnosed positive. In Lautoka, the fourteen case of the sister of Fiji's first case was confirmed positive of the disease. She is also the mother of the one-year-old boy who was also confirmed positive of the disease earlier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/two-more-covid-19-cases-confirmed/|title=Two more COVID-19 cases confirmed|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, Fiji confirmed its fifteenth case, a 33-year-old man from Lautoka. This case is linked to the first case of the flight attendant. He is the husband of the fifth case.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/one-more-covid-19-case-confirmed-total-up-to-15/ | title=One more COVID-19 case confirmed, total up to 15 | work=FBC News | date= 07 April 2020| accessdate=07 April 2020}}</ref> Police Commissioner [[Law enforcement in Fiji| Sitiveni Qiliho]] had confirmed that a police investigation would proceed for the 27-year-old flight attendant from Lautoka who was the first confirmed COVID-19 case and the ninth case a 54-year-old Labasa man for allegedly breaching the Public Health Regulations.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.fijivillage.com/news/27-year-old-flight-attendant-and-the-54-year-old-Labasa-man-expected-to-be-investigated-for-allegedly-breaching-the-Public-Health-Regulations-f54xr8/?fbclid=IwAR1UZtuIVggxn6ZoBz34rT1V97HgLqcBkY_v7l_zxOpNVMk_oY6IX_q0TSs | title=27y/o flight attendant and 54y/o Labasa man expected to be investigated for allegedly breaching the Public Health Regulations | work=FijiVillage | date= 07 April 2020| accessdate=07 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Summary of Cases==\n* First case: 27-year-old male from Lautoka.\n* Second case: 58-year-old female from Lautoka.\n* Third case: 1-year-old male from Lautoka.\n* Fourth case: 28-year-old male from Suva.\n*Fifth case: 31-year-old female from Lautoka.\n* Sixth case: 21-year-old female from Suva.\n* Seventh case: 33-year-old male from Suva.\n*Eighth case: 11-year-old female from Suva.\n* Ninth case: 54-year-old male from Labasa.\n* Tenth case: 39-year-old female from Lautoka.\n* Eleventh case: 20-year-old female from Nadi.\n* Twelfth case: 25-year-old female from Labasa.\n* Thirteenth case: The wife of the ninth case from Labasa.\n* Fourteenth case: Sister of the first patient and mother of third patient from Lautoka.\n* Fifteenth case: 33-year-old male and husband of the fifth case from Lautoka\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |COVID-19 Cases in Fiji broken down in gender as of April 7 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Gender\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Female\n|9\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | \nMale \n|6\n|0\n|-\n\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{Number format|15|separator=}}\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{Number format|0|separator=}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |COVID-19 Cases in Fiji broken down in division  as of April 7, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Division\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Western Division]]\n|8\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Central Division]]\n|4\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Northern Division]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{Number format|15|separator=}}\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{Number format|0|separator=}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |COVID-19 Cases in Fiji broken down in cities/towns as of April 7, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Location\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Lautoka]]\n|7\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Suva]]\n|4\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Labasa]]\n|